G = {}

def hd(t,tl): return f'<h2>{t}</h2>\n<p class="tl">{tl}</p>\n'
def s(t): return f'<h3>{t}</h3>\n'
def p(t): return f'<p>{t}</p>\n'
def hl(t,c=''): return f'<div class="hl {c}">{t}</div>\n'
def cols(a,b): return f'<div class="co"><div>{a}</div><div>{b}</div></div>\n'
def h4(t): return f'<h4>{t}</h4>\n'

# ===== CHARTS 02-06: GLOBAL DEVELOPMENT =====

G["02"] = hd("Fertility vs Longevity","The most consequential transformation in human history, compressed into 33 seconds.") + s("Reading the Axes") + p("<b>X-axis: Total Fertility Rate (TFR)</b>, the average number of children a woman would bear at current age-specific birth rates. The critical threshold is <em>2.1</em> (replacement level; the 0.1 accounts for child mortality). Above 2.1 = population growth; below = eventual decline without immigration. <b>Y-axis: Life expectancy at birth</b>. <b>Bubble size</b> = population; <b>color</b> = continent.") + s("The Demographic Transition Model") + p("The global migration from upper-left (high fertility, low longevity) to lower-right (low fertility, high longevity) is the <b>Demographic Transition</b> (Thompson 1929, Notestein 1945). Four stages: <b>Stage 1</b> (pre-modern): high birth and death rates, stable population. <b>Stage 2</b>: death rates fall (medicine, sanitation), births remain high, population explodes. <b>Stage 3</b>: births fall (urbanization, women's education, contraception), growth slows. <b>Stage 4</b>: both rates low, population stable or declining.") + hl("The causal mechanisms of fertility decline: (1) <b>Child survival</b>: when parents are confident children will survive, they have fewer (Caldwell 1982). (2) <b>Women's education</b>: each year of female secondary schooling reduces fertility by 0.3-0.5 births (UNESCO 2022). (3) <b>Contraceptive access</b>: unmet need remains ~25% in Sub-Saharan Africa. (4) <b>Urbanization</b>: in rural economies, children are labor assets; in cities, they are costs. The rural-to-urban transition is a fertility transition.","g") + s("Spatial Wave of Transition") + p("Europe and East Asia completed the transition first (1960s-1990s). Latin America and South Asia followed (1980s-2010s). <b>Sub-Saharan Africa is the last major region</b>, with the transition accelerating post-2000. Within Africa, coastal/southern states (Kenya, Ghana, South Africa) are further along than Sahelian/Central states (Niger, Chad, DRC). The spatial gradient follows the broader latitude-development pattern visible in Charts 23 and 25.") + s("Anthropological Significance") + p("For 99% of human existence, women spent most of their adult lives pregnant or nursing. The fertility decline represents a <b>fundamental change in the lived experience of womanhood</b>. In post-transition societies, women spend <10% of adult years in childbearing, freeing capacity for education, work, and political participation. This is not merely demographic; it is a transformation of gender relations with implications for every domain of human life.") + s("Policy Implications") + hl("<b>For high-fertility countries</b>: invest in girls' secondary education ($300-500/year in Sub-Saharan Africa, 10-15x return). <b>For low-fertility countries</b> (Japan 1.2, Korea 0.7): subsidized childcare, parental leave, immigration. Evidence suggests that once TFR drops below ~1.5, recovery is very difficult ('low-fertility trap', Lutz et al. 2006). <b>The remaining high-fertility countries</b> (Niger, Chad, Somalia, DRC, Mali) will determine whether world population peaks at 9 billion or 11 billion. Their trajectories depend almost entirely on whether girls' education scales in the next two decades.","w")

G["03"] = hd("Child Mortality vs Wealth","Every dot moving downward represents thousands of children who survived to their fifth birthday.") + s("Understanding the Variables") + cols(h4("Under-5 Mortality (Y-axis)") + p("Deaths per 1,000 live births before age 5. Value of 200 = 1 in 5 children dies. Below 10 = developed-world norm. This metric captures the combined impact of nutrition, sanitation, healthcare access, and infectious disease."), h4("GDP per Capita, PPP (X-axis, log)") + p("Log scale because the relationship is genuinely logarithmic: the first $1,000 of income buys ~50 fewer deaths per 1,000. Going from $50,000 to $100,000 reduces mortality by ~0.5. A linear scale would compress all low-income countries into an unreadable strip.")) + s("What Saved the Children") + p("The global decline from 12.7 million child deaths/year (1990) to 5.0 million (2023) was driven by: <b>Oral rehydration therapy</b> (treating diarrhea, the leading killer), <b>vaccination campaigns</b> (measles deaths fell 73%), <b>insecticide-treated bed nets</b> (malaria), and <b>improved nutrition</b> (breastfeeding promotion, micronutrient supplementation). The acceleration post-2000 coincides with the Millennium Development Goals, which channeled international funding and political will toward child survival.") + s("Exceptional Countries") + hl("<b>Bangladesh</b> (GDP ~$8,000, mortality ~27) achieves results far below what the curve predicts, through community health workers, oral rehydration, and vaccination. <b>Rwanda</b> achieved similar results through performance-based healthcare financing. <b>Equatorial Guinea</b> (GDP ~$16,000, mortality ~80) shows the opposite: oil wealth not translated into public health. <b>Lesson</b>: wealth is neither necessary nor sufficient for child survival; it is the allocation of resources that matters.","g") + s("Spatial Pattern of Remaining Child Death") + p("Remaining high-mortality countries cluster in: (1) the <b>Sahel belt</b> (Mali, Niger, Chad), where drought, food insecurity, and weak governance compound health challenges, and (2) <b>conflict zones</b> (Yemen, Somalia, South Sudan), where violence destroys health infrastructure. Both zones are characterized by <b>spatial isolation</b>: long distances, few roads, limited telecommunications.") + s("Policy: Cost-Effectiveness Ranking") + hl("Most cost-effective interventions per DALY (disability-adjusted life year) saved: (1) Childhood vaccination ~$10-15/DALY, (2) ORS + zinc for diarrhea ~$25, (3) Insecticide bed nets ~$30, (4) Breastfeeding promotion ~$50. <b>Fund these in order before investing in expensive tertiary hospitals</b>. The MDG-era acceleration proves coordinated international goals with funding commitments work.","w")

G["04"] = hd("Country Trajectory Traces","Not all development paths go up and to the right. Some dip, stall, or spiral.") + s("Reading the Traces") + p("14 key nations traced on the GDP (log, X) vs life expectancy (Y) plane over multiple decades. Each line = one country's path through development space. <b>Rightward = richer</b>, <b>upward = healthier</b>, <b>leftward = economic contraction</b>, <b>downward = health crisis</b>. Scatter points mark specific years along each trajectory.") + s("The Trajectories That Teach") + hl("<b>China</b>: the most dramatic rightward leap in modern history. From $800 GDP per capita in 1990 to $22,000+ by 2023, driven by export-led industrialization, massive infrastructure investment, and urbanization. Life expectancy rose from 69 to 78. <b>Botswana/South Africa</b>: downward loops during the HIV/AIDS epidemic (1990s-2000s), losing 10-15 years of life expectancy before antiretroviral therapy enabled recovery. The loop shape reveals both the crisis and the response. <b>Rwanda</b>: a sharp downward spike in 1994 (genocide killed ~800,000 people) followed by one of the fastest recoveries in history, demonstrating that governance and institutional rebuilding can overcome catastrophic shocks. <b>Venezuela</b>: leftward movement in the 2010s (economic contraction under hyperinflation), a rare case of a middle-income country regressing.","g") + s("The Science: Path Dependency in Development") + p("The traces reveal <b>path dependency</b> (Arthur 1994, Acemoglu and Robinson 2012): a country's current position is shaped by its historical trajectory, not just its current endowments. Countries that built human capital early (education, healthcare) created positive feedback loops: educated populations demanded better governance, which funded more education. Countries trapped in extractive institutions created negative loops: elites extracted resources, preventing investment in human capital. The traces make these loops visible as upward spirals (virtuous) or stagnation/regression (vicious).") + s("Policy Implications") + hl("<b>Development is not monotonic</b>. Health system resilience (the ability to absorb shocks and recover) is as important as baseline trajectory. Countries should invest in both <em>growth</em> (the rightward push) and <em>resilience</em> (epidemic preparedness, conflict prevention, climate adaptation, financial buffer funds). The HIV/AIDS dip teaches that a single disease can erase decades of progress; the subsequent recovery teaches that international cooperation (PEPFAR, the Global Fund) can reverse even catastrophic setbacks.","w")

G["05"] = hd("Continental Trends","Health is converging. Wealth is diverging. The paradox that defines our era.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Three panels showing <b>population-weighted</b> averages by continent for GDP per capita (left), life expectancy (center), and fertility rate (right) over 1990-2023. Population weighting means each line reflects what the <em>average person</em> on that continent experiences, not the average country. This makes China and India dominate Asian averages and Nigeria dominate African averages.") + s("The Convergence-Divergence Paradox") + hl("<b>Life expectancy is converging</b>: Africa's line is rising faster than Europe's, narrowing the gap from ~25 years (1990) to ~15 years (2023). This means health interventions (vaccines, primary care, bed nets) have been <b>globally equitable</b> in their impact. <b>GDP per capita is diverging</b>: the gap between Africa and Europe/Americas is widening in absolute terms. Markets concentrate wealth geographically; health technologies diffuse more evenly. <b>Fertility is converging</b>: Africa's rate is falling toward the global mean, driven by urbanization and education. This is the central paradox of modern development: <b>the world is becoming more equal in health but less equal in wealth</b>.") + s("Spatial Interpretation") + p("The continental averages mask enormous within-continent variation. Africa's life expectancy average is pulled up by North Africa (72-76 years) and down by West/Central Africa (55-65 years). Asia's GDP average is pulled up by China and East Asia and down by South Asia and Central Asia. The continental framing, while useful for overview, should be complemented by the country-level charts (01-03) for precision.") + s("Policy") + hl("Health convergence proves that <b>targeted international interventions can overcome structural inequality</b>. GAVI (vaccines), the Global Fund (HIV/malaria/TB), and WHO programmes have demonstrably narrowed the health gap. GDP divergence proves that <b>markets alone will not equalize wealth</b>. Trade policy, technology transfer, infrastructure investment, and institutional reform are needed to close the economic gap. The fact that one gap is closing while the other widens suggests fundamentally different dynamics: health improvement is driven by technology diffusion (which crosses borders easily), while wealth improvement requires institutional change (which is locally specific).","w")

G["06"] = hd("Income Distribution Shift","The disappearing 'two humps' that Hans Rosling spent his career teaching the world about.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Population-weighted income distribution across the world at different time points. The <b>X-axis is log income</b> (each gridline = 10x increase). <b>Area under each curve</b> = proportional to population at that income level. In 1995, there were <b>two distinct peaks</b> ('humps'): a poor-world peak around $1,000-$2,000 and a rich-world peak around $20,000-$40,000. By 2020, these have substantially merged into <b>one broad peak</b> centered around $5,000-$15,000.") + s("What Drove the Merge") + hl("<b>China</b> (~1.4 billion people) shifted from $2,000 to $18,000+ per capita in this period, moving an enormous population mass from the left peak toward the center. <b>India</b> (~1.4 billion) shifted from $1,500 to $8,000+, adding to the center. Together, these two countries account for ~36% of humanity. Their economic growth physically dragged the bimodal distribution toward unimodal. The remaining left tail (extreme poor) is increasingly concentrated in <b>Sub-Saharan Africa</b> and <b>conflict zones</b>.","g") + s("Rosling's Legacy and Remaining Challenges") + p("Hans Rosling spent decades arguing that the 'developed vs developing' binary was outdated. This chart vindicates him. But the merge is incomplete: the left tail represents ~700 million people in extreme poverty, overwhelmingly in places with the <b>most difficult governance and geographic environments</b>: landlocked Sahelian states, conflict zones, and regions with tropical disease burdens. The 'last mile' of poverty reduction is harder because these populations face compounding spatial, institutional, and environmental disadvantages that market-driven growth alone cannot address.") + hl("Policy: the shift from bimodal to unimodal has profound implications for international development. The era of 'rich countries helping poor countries' is giving way to a more nuanced reality where most of the world is middle-income and the extreme poor are concentrated in specific, identifiable geographic zones requiring spatially targeted interventions.","w")

# ===== CHARTS 07-08: CORAL/OCEANS =====

G["07"] = hd("Reef Bleaching Hotspots","A requiem for the underwater rainforests we are losing.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("27 major coral reef systems plotted on a dark ocean map. <b>Marker size</b> = reef area (km2). <b>Color = threat level</b>: <em>Critical</em> (>50% coral cover lost, red), <em>High</em> (significant recent bleaching, orange), <em>Medium</em> (yellow), <em>Low</em> (green). Data compiled from NOAA Coral Reef Watch, UNEP World Conservation Monitoring Centre, and AIMS Long-Term Monitoring.") + s("The Science of Coral Bleaching") + hl("Coral bleaching occurs when ocean temperatures rise <b>1-2C above the seasonal maximum</b> for sustained periods (4-8 weeks). Corals are symbiotic organisms: the coral animal hosts photosynthetic algae (zooxanthellae) that provide 80-90% of its energy through photosynthesis. Thermal stress causes the coral to expel these algae, turning white ('bleaching'). If temperatures return to normal within 2-3 weeks, corals can reabsorb algae and recover. If stress persists, the coral starves and dies. Mass bleaching events occur when entire reef systems experience simultaneous thermal stress, typically during El Nino events compounded by anthropogenic ocean warming.") + s("Spatial Distribution of Threat") + p("<b>Critical reefs</b> concentrate in: the <b>Caribbean</b> (where warming is compounded by disease, pollution, and overfishing) and the <b>Coral Triangle</b> (Indonesia, Philippines, Papua New Guinea), the most biodiverse marine region on Earth. The <b>Great Barrier Reef</b> experienced mass bleaching in 2016, 2017, 2020, 2022, and 2024. <b>Indian Ocean</b> reefs (Maldives, Seychelles, Andaman & Nicobar) face increasing thermal stress as the Indian Ocean warms faster than the global average.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Marine Protected Areas</b> (MPAs) reduce local stressors (overfishing, sedimentation, pollution) and can enhance reef resilience to thermal stress. But MPAs <b>cannot prevent</b> bleaching caused by global ocean warming. The Paris Agreement's 1.5C warming target is effectively a <b>reef survival threshold</b>. At 1.5C: 70-90% of tropical reefs will experience severe bleaching annually. At 2C: 99% will bleach annually. Current trajectory: 2.5-3C by 2100. The implication: most tropical reefs alive today will not exist by 2070 under current emissions scenarios. Conservation must shift from 'protect and recover' to 'adapt and triage': identifying genetically heat-tolerant populations for conservation and assisted gene flow.","w")

G["08"] = hd("Ocean Temperature: The Fever Chart of a Warming Planet","The baseline is rising. Today's 'normal' would have been an emergency in the 1980s.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Global sea surface temperature (SST) anomaly from 1980 to 2024, measured as deviation from the 1971-2000 baseline average. <b>Positive values</b> = warmer than the historical 30-year mean. The <b>filled area</b> below the line emphasizes cumulative warming. <b>Annotations</b> mark the four mass coral bleaching events (1998, 2010, 2016, 2024).") + s("The Physics of Ocean Warming") + p("Oceans absorb approximately <b>93% of excess heat</b> trapped by greenhouse gases. This makes SST the most direct thermometer of anthropogenic warming. The upward trend is unambiguous and accelerating: the rate of warming post-2000 is approximately double the 1980-2000 rate. The anomaly reached +0.5C above baseline in the early 2000s and +1.0C by 2024. Because the baseline itself (1971-2000) was already warmer than pre-industrial oceans, the true warming relative to pre-industrial is approximately +1.2-1.5C at the surface.") + s("Accelerating Frequency of Crises") + hl("Mass bleaching event intervals: <b>1998 to 2010 = 12 years</b>. <b>2010 to 2016 = 6 years</b>. <b>2016 to 2024 = 8 years</b>. Coral recovery from a mass bleaching event requires <b>10-15 years</b> of cool conditions for regrowth. If bleaching occurs every 6-8 years, reefs <b>cannot recover between events</b>, leading to permanent structural degradation. The tightening interval is the single most alarming trend in marine ecology.","w") + s("Policy Implications") + p("Two parallel strategies are needed: (1) <b>Global</b>: rapid decarbonization to limit warming to 1.5C (the reef survival threshold). Every tenth of a degree matters. (2) <b>Local</b>: reducing non-thermal stressors (overfishing, sedimentation, nutrient pollution) through Marine Protected Areas and watershed management, which enhance reef resilience to thermal events. The economic stakes are enormous: coral reefs provide ecosystem services (fisheries, coastal protection, tourism) valued at <b>$375 billion/year</b> globally. Their loss would devastate the economies of Small Island Developing States.")

# ===== CHARTS 09-12: PEOPLE & POVERTY =====

G["09"] = hd("Urbanization","The largest migration in human history is happening right now, and most of us are not paying attention.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated world choropleth: urban population as % of total, 1990-2022. <b>Darker color = more urban</b>. Step through the animation to watch three decades of rural-to-urban migration. Key transitions: China 26% to 64%, India 26% to 35%, Sub-Saharan Africa 28% to 42%.") + s("The Spatial Science of Urbanization") + hl("Urbanization follows predictable spatial patterns described by <b>central place theory</b> (Christaller 1933) and <b>rank-size distribution</b> (Zipf 1949). Cities form hierarchical systems: a few megacities (>10M), more medium cities (1-5M), and many small towns. In well-functioning urban systems, growth is distributed across the hierarchy. In <b>primate city systems</b> (common in developing countries), one dominant city absorbs most urban growth, creating congestion, inequality, and spatial imbalance (Bangkok, Lagos, Lima). <b>Secondary cities</b> (500K-2M) are growing fastest globally but receive the least planning attention.") + s("Policy: The Critical Window") + hl("Countries entering the <b>30-50% urbanization range</b> (current Sub-Saharan Africa, parts of South Asia) face a critical policy window. Investment decisions made NOW in transit, housing, sanitation, and urban planning will determine whether urbanization produces <b>prosperity</b> (as in East Asia, where urban investment preceded mass migration) or <b>slums</b> (as in much of South Asia and Africa, where migration outpaced infrastructure). <b>The cost of retrofitting</b> unplanned urban growth is 3-5x the cost of planning ahead. Every year of delay increases the ultimate infrastructure bill. The spatial pattern matters: investing in <b>secondary cities</b> (not just capitals) can distribute growth more equitably and prevent primate city overload.","w") + s("Anthropological Dimensions") + p("Urbanization transforms every dimension of human life: family structures (nuclear replaces extended), economic activity (formal wage labor replaces subsistence agriculture), social networks (chosen communities replace kinship groups), gender relations (women gain economic autonomy through formal employment), and political participation (urban residents are more likely to vote, protest, and organize). The animation captures a transformation that is remaking the social fabric of Asia and Africa in real time.")

G["10"] = hd("Slum Population","For a billion people, the city of opportunity is a city of tin roofs and open sewers.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of the percentage of urban population living in <b>slum conditions</b>. <b>Darker color = higher slum prevalence</b>. Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia show the highest rates, with several countries exceeding 60%.") + s("Defining 'Slum': The UN-Habitat Criteria") + hl("<b>Slum household</b> (UN-Habitat): a dwelling lacking ONE OR MORE of: (1) <b>Durable structure</b> (permanent walls, roof, floor), (2) <b>Sufficient living area</b> (<3 people per room), (3) <b>Improved water</b> (piped, borehole, or protected spring within 200m), (4) <b>Improved sanitation</b> (flush toilet or ventilated pit latrine, not shared with >20 people), (5) <b>Security of tenure</b> (formal ownership or rental agreement). The definition is deliberately broad: lacking even ONE criterion qualifies as a slum. This means 'slum' encompasses a spectrum from simple lack of a rental agreement to complete absence of all five services.") + s("The Geography of Informal Settlement") + p("Slum formation follows predictable spatial patterns. In most developing-world cities, informal settlements concentrate in: (1) <b>floodplains and riverbanks</b> (cheap because flood-prone; Dharavi in Mumbai, Makoko in Lagos), (2) <b>steep hillsides</b> (cheap because landslide-prone; favelas in Rio, Kibera's edges in Nairobi), (3) <b>peri-urban fringes</b> (on the expanding edge of the city, where formal land use controls are weakest), and (4) <b>industrial zones</b> (near factories, for labor proximity). These locations share a common feature: they are <b>land that formal markets reject</b>, which is why they are available to the poor.") + s("Policy: Upgrading vs. Demolition") + hl("<b>Slum upgrading</b> (providing water, sanitation, paved paths, electricity, and land tenure to existing settlements) costs $500-2,000 per household and yields 10-20x returns in health, productivity, and property values. <b>Demolition and relocation</b> costs $5,000-15,000 per household and often <em>increases</em> poverty by destroying social networks and livelihood proximity. The evidence overwhelmingly favors upgrading. Medecin (2013) showed that Mumbai's slum upgrading programmes increased household incomes by 30% and reduced child mortality by 40%. <b>Tenure security</b> is the single most impactful intervention: when families know they will not be evicted, they invest in their own housing, often tripling the value of their dwelling within 5 years.","w")

G["11"] = hd("Extreme Poverty","700 million people still survive on less than the price of a cup of coffee per day.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of the population below the <b>World Bank extreme poverty line of $2.15/day</b> (recently updated from $1.90), adjusted for purchasing power parity. <b>Darker color = higher poverty rate</b>.") + s("Understanding the Poverty Line") + hl("$2.15/day (PPP) represents the <b>absolute minimum needed for basic survival</b>: enough calories to avoid starvation, but not enough for adequate nutrition, healthcare, education, or housing. It is set as the average national poverty line of the world's 15 poorest countries. Living below this line means chronic hunger, no healthcare, no education for children, and extreme vulnerability to any shock (illness, drought, conflict). The PPP adjustment means this line buys equivalent goods in all countries: $2.15 in India buys roughly what $2.15 buys in the United States in terms of basic necessities.") + s("Spatial Concentration") + p("Extreme poverty has become increasingly <b>geographically concentrated</b>. In 1990, it was spread across South Asia, East Asia, and Sub-Saharan Africa. By 2023, East Asia has nearly eliminated it (China alone lifted ~800 million people out of extreme poverty), South Asia has dramatically reduced it (India from 46% to ~12%), and <b>Sub-Saharan Africa bears the overwhelming remaining burden</b>. Within Africa, the worst-affected areas are: the <b>Sahel</b> (structural food insecurity), <b>Great Lakes region</b> (conflict-driven poverty), and <b>southern Mozambique/Madagascar</b> (climate vulnerability). These are all areas with compounding geographic disadvantages: landlocked, arid, conflict-prone, or climate-exposed.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Cash transfers</b> (GiveDirectly model: unconditional $500-1,000 to extreme poor households) show sustained poverty reduction in randomized controlled trials. <b>Agricultural investment</b> (improved seeds, irrigation, market access) addresses the structural basis of rural poverty. <b>Conflict resolution</b> is prerequisite in many worst-affected countries: you cannot reduce poverty in an active war zone. <b>Spatial targeting</b> is increasingly sophisticated: satellite imagery (night lights, roof materials) can identify extreme poverty at village level, enabling precise targeting of interventions.","w")

G["12"] = hd("Gini Inequality","Not how big the pie is, but how it is sliced.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of the <b>Gini coefficient</b> (0 = perfect equality, 100 = one person has everything). <b>Darker = more unequal</b>.") + s("How Gini Is Calculated") + hl("The Gini coefficient is derived from the <b>Lorenz curve</b>, which plots the cumulative share of income (Y-axis) against the cumulative share of population ranked by income (X-axis). In a perfectly equal society, the Lorenz curve is a 45-degree diagonal (the bottom 10% earn 10% of income, the bottom 50% earn 50%, etc.). The Gini coefficient is the <b>ratio of the area between the actual Lorenz curve and the diagonal</b> to the total area under the diagonal. <code>Gini = A / (A + B)</code>, where A = area between the curve and diagonal, B = area under the curve. Values: <b>25-30</b> (Scandinavia, very equal), <b>35-40</b> (Western Europe, moderately equal), <b>40-45</b> (US, China, moderate inequality), <b>50-63</b> (South Africa, Brazil, extreme inequality).") + s("What Gini Tells Us (and What It Misses)") + p("Gini captures <em>relative</em> income distribution but misses several things: (1) It does not distinguish between inequality at the top (billionaires pulling away) and bottom (extreme poverty). Two countries can have the same Gini with very different poverty rates. (2) It does not capture wealth inequality (which is always higher than income inequality because wealth accumulates). (3) It does not capture spatial inequality (urban-rural gaps, regional disparities). For India-specific analysis, the <b>Theil index</b> (which can be decomposed into between-state and within-state components) is more informative.") + s("The Health Cost of Inequality") + hl("Wilkinson and Pickett (2009, <em>The Spirit Level</em>) demonstrated that among wealthy nations, <b>more unequal societies have worse outcomes on virtually every social indicator</b>: life expectancy, mental health, drug abuse, obesity, educational performance, imprisonment rates, teenage pregnancy, and social trust. This holds even controlling for absolute income, meaning that inequality itself is damaging, not just poverty. The mechanism is believed to be <b>psychosocial stress</b>: living in a highly unequal society generates chronic stress from status competition, social comparison, and perceived unfairness.","g") + s("Policy") + hl("Gini reduction tools: (1) <b>Progressive taxation</b> (higher rates on higher incomes). (2) <b>Universal public services</b> (education, healthcare, transport) that disproportionately benefit the poor. (3) <b>Minimum wage laws</b> and <b>labor protections</b>. (4) <b>Land reform</b> (particularly relevant in Latin America and South Asia where land concentration drives income concentration). (5) <b>Conditional cash transfers</b> (Brazil's Bolsa Familia reduced Gini by ~2 points over a decade). Latin America's declining Gini since 2000 proves these tools work; China's rising Gini proves that rapid GDP growth without redistribution increases inequality.","w")

# ===== CHARTS 13-21: TECHNOLOGY, MONEY, ENVIRONMENT =====

G["13"] = hd("Internet Usage","Watching the digital revolution sweep the planet in 22 years.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated choropleth: <b>internet users as % of population</b>, 2000-2022. Increasing color intensity = higher penetration. Step through the animation to watch the digital revolution propagate from North to South, rich to poor.") + s("Spatial Diffusion of the Internet") + hl("The internet's spread follows a modified <b>hierarchical diffusion model</b> (Hagerstrand 1967): adoption starts in <em>innovation centers</em> (Silicon Valley, Scandinavia, East Asian tech hubs), spreads to national capitals, then secondary cities, then rural areas. Within Sub-Saharan Africa, coastal capitals (Lagos, Nairobi, Accra) reached 50% penetration a decade before interior regions. The late-stage acceleration (2015-2022) in Africa was driven by <b>mobile internet leapfrogging</b> fixed-line infrastructure: smartphones + 3G/4G towers are cheaper to deploy than fiber-optic cable. By 2022, most internet access in developing countries is mobile-first.") + s("The Digital Divide as Spatial Inequality") + p("The remaining offline population (~2.6 billion people) is concentrated in: (1) <b>rural Sub-Saharan Africa</b> (tower coverage gaps, electricity gaps, affordability gaps), (2) <b>rural South Asia</b> (similar barriers plus language barriers and low digital literacy), (3) <b>conflict zones</b> (infrastructure destruction). <b>Within-country digital divides</b> often exceed between-country divides: in Nigeria, Lagos has 80%+ penetration while rural Zamfara has <20%.") + s("Policy") + hl("The World Bank estimates that a <b>10% increase in broadband penetration</b> in developing countries corresponds to a <b>1.4% increase in GDP growth</b>. The returns come from: telemedicine (reducing healthcare travel costs), mobile banking (financial inclusion for the unbanked), agricultural market information (farmers getting real-time prices rather than being exploited by middlemen), and distance education. <b>Universal broadband</b> (the UN Broadband Commission's target: affordable access at <2% of monthly income by 2025) requires: tower infrastructure in underserved areas, spectrum allocation for rural operators, device affordability programmes, and digital literacy training. The estimated cost of connecting the remaining 2.6 billion people is $400-500 billion, roughly the cost of one year of global military spending.","w")

G["14"] = hd("Electricity Access","In the dark, everything is harder: studying, healing, working, cooking.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>% of population with electricity access</b>. Sub-Saharan Africa dominates the map with the lowest rates: Chad (11%), Burundi (11%), South Sudan (8%), Central African Republic (15%). India achieved near-universal access by 2022 through the Saubhagya scheme.") + s("Energy Poverty: A Spatial Phenomenon") + hl("Electricity access follows <b>population density</b> closely. Grid extension is economically viable where population density exceeds ~100 people/km2. Below that threshold, the per-household cost of transmission lines becomes prohibitive ($1,000-5,000 per household). Most of Sub-Saharan Africa outside major cities falls below this density threshold. The <b>spatial solution</b>: off-grid and mini-grid systems. Solar home systems ($100-300 per household) provide basic lighting, phone charging, and radio. Mini-grids (serving 50-500 households) can power small businesses. East Africa's pay-as-you-go solar revolution (M-KOPA, d.light) demonstrates that private-sector solutions can scale faster than government grid extension in dispersed populations.") + s("The Cascade of Deprivation") + p("Lack of electricity creates a <b>cascade of deprivation</b>: (1) <b>Education</b>: children cannot study after dark (sunset is ~6pm year-round near the equator). Kerosene lamps provide dim, expensive, unhealthy light. (2) <b>Healthcare</b>: vaccines require refrigeration (cold chain). Surgery requires reliable power. Rural clinics without electricity cannot store medicines or operate equipment. (3) <b>Economic activity</b>: businesses cannot operate machinery, refrigerate goods, or use telecommunications after dark. (4) <b>Indoor air quality</b>: without electricity, families use biomass (wood, charcoal, dung) for cooking, causing ~2.6 million deaths/year from indoor air pollution, overwhelmingly women and children.") + s("Policy") + hl("The <b>most cost-effective pathway</b> to universal electricity access in Sub-Saharan Africa is a mixed strategy: (1) Grid extension in dense urban and peri-urban areas. (2) Mini-grids for medium-density towns and villages. (3) Solar home systems for dispersed rural populations. The IEA estimates that universal access by 2030 would cost $35-40 billion/year (less than 3% of global energy investment). The return is enormous: the World Bank estimates that electricity access increases household income by 15-25% and children's study time by 40-60 minutes/day.","w")

G["15"] = hd("Mobile Phone Subscriptions","The most equitably distributed technology in human history.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>mobile subscriptions per 100 people</b>. Values exceeding 100 indicate multiple SIM cards per person (common where competing networks have different coverage zones or pricing plans). Even the poorest Sub-Saharan African countries show 40-80 subscriptions per 100.") + s("The Leapfrog Effect") + hl("Mobile telephony is a textbook case of <b>technological leapfrogging</b> (Steinmueller 2001): developing countries skipped the landline-telephone era entirely and jumped directly to mobile. A mobile tower serving a 10km radius costs ~$50,000 to install and covers thousands of users. Laying copper wire to each household costs $500-2,000 per connection. The economics made mobile the only viable telecommunications option for most of Africa and South Asia. By 2023, there are more mobile subscriptions in Sub-Saharan Africa than people with access to clean water. This is not a paradox of misplaced priorities; it reflects the fact that mobile infrastructure is dramatically cheaper per user than water infrastructure.") + s("Mobile as Development Platform") + p("<b>Mobile money</b> (M-Pesa, launched Kenya 2007): 50+ million users in East Africa. Enables savings, credit, insurance, and wage payment without bank accounts. Reduced extreme poverty in Kenya by 2 percentage points (Suri and Jack, 2016). <b>Mobile health (mHealth)</b>: SMS-based appointment reminders increase clinic attendance by 25-40%. Mobile-phone-based diagnostics (malaria rapid tests photographed and AI-analyzed) are scaling. <b>Agricultural market information</b>: farmers receiving real-time price data via SMS earn 15-30% more because they can negotiate with middlemen from a position of knowledge.") + s("Policy") + hl("Mobile penetration is now high enough in virtually all countries that it can serve as the <b>primary delivery channel</b> for government services: tax payment, social welfare disbursement (India's Direct Benefit Transfer reaches 800+ million people via mobile-linked bank accounts), voter registration, land title registration, and health information. Governments should design all new citizen-facing services <b>mobile-first</b>.","w")

G["16"] = hd("GDP per Capita","The map that defines the global conversation about development, and all the things it leaves out.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>GDP per capita in Purchasing Power Parity (PPP) dollars</b>. PPP adjusts for local price levels: $1,000 in India buys more food, housing, and services than $1,000 in Switzerland. Without PPP, the map would dramatically overstate deprivation in low-cost countries.") + s("The Gap") + hl("The range spans <b>two orders of magnitude</b>: Burundi (~$800) to Luxembourg (~$130,000). A person born in Luxembourg has, on average, <b>160x the economic resources</b> of a person born in Burundi. This is not merely a difference in luxury goods; it translates into differences in life expectancy (55 vs 82 years), child mortality (50 vs 2 per 1,000), education (3 vs 14 years of schooling), and virtually every other measure of human welfare.") + s("Spatial Patterns: The North-South Divide and Its Exceptions") + p("The dominant pattern is a <b>North-South wealth gradient</b>, with temperate Northern Hemisphere countries overwhelmingly wealthier than tropical Southern Hemisphere countries. Exceptions that reveal the limits of geographic determinism: <b>Singapore</b> (1 degree latitude, GDP $130K), <b>Gulf states</b> (tropical but resource-rich), <b>Botswana</b> (tropical but well-governed), and <b>Australia/New Zealand</b> (Southern Hemisphere but settler colonies with imported institutions). These exceptions point to the <b>institutions hypothesis</b> (Acemoglu et al. 2001): geography matters, but institutional quality mediates its effects.") + s("What GDP Misses") + hl("<b>GDP per capita is the standard welfare proxy but has critical limitations</b>: (1) It misses <em>inequality</em>: a country with high average income can have most people poor (Qatar: high GDP, vast worker exploitation). (2) It misses <em>unpaid labor</em>: women's domestic and care work (estimated at 10-40% of GDP if valued) is invisible. (3) It misses <em>environmental degradation</em>: deforestation is counted as economic activity (timber revenue) rather than asset destruction. (4) It misses <em>well-being</em>: the US has the highest GDP among large nations but ranks 46th in life expectancy and reports high rates of loneliness, addiction, and mental illness. Alternative measures (HDI, GNH, Genuine Progress Indicator) attempt to address these gaps.","g")

G["17"] = hd("Trade Openness","How connected is your economy to the rest of the world?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>total trade (exports + imports) as percentage of GDP</b>. High values indicate deep integration into global supply chains.") + s("Understanding Extreme Values") + hl("<b>Singapore (>300%)</b>, <b>Hong Kong (>350%)</b>, and <b>Luxembourg (>400%)</b> show values exceeding 100% because they are <em>entrepot economies</em>: goods pass through their ports/airports and are re-exported, inflating trade relative to domestic production. A container of electronics manufactured in China may pass through Singapore's port, getting counted in Singapore's trade statistics without being consumed there. <b>Large continental economies</b> (US ~25%, Brazil ~30%, Japan ~35%, India ~40%) show lower ratios despite massive absolute trade volumes because their large domestic markets absorb most production.") + s("Geography of Trade Integration") + p("Trade openness follows <b>two geographic patterns</b>: (1) <em>Size effect</em>: smaller countries are more open because their domestic markets are too small to sustain diversified production (they must trade to access goods they do not produce). (2) <em>Location effect</em>: countries on major maritime trade routes (Singapore, Netherlands, UAE) or in integrated economic blocs (EU member states) show higher openness. Landlocked countries (see Chart 27) face structural barriers to trade integration.") + s("Policy: Trade and Development") + hl("Openness correlates with long-run growth (Dollar and Kraay 2004), but also with <b>vulnerability to global shocks</b>: the 2008 financial crisis hit open economies hardest. The 2020 COVID supply chain disruption demonstrated that extreme trade dependence without strategic reserves creates fragility. <b>Optimal strategy for developing countries</b>: reduce tariff barriers to increase market access, invest in trade-facilitating infrastructure (ports, customs digitization, trade finance), while maintaining capacity for <b>counter-cyclical fiscal policy</b> and <b>strategic reserves</b> of essential goods (food, fuel, medicine). The WTO's Trade Facilitation Agreement (2017) estimates that full implementation would reduce trade costs by 14.3% for developing countries.","w")

G["18"] = hd("Remittances","The invisible river of money flowing from the Global North to the Global South.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>personal remittances received as % of GDP</b>. High dependency (>20%) indicates economies where a significant fraction of working-age adults has migrated abroad.") + s("The Scale of Remittance Flows") + hl("Global remittances to developing countries: <b>~$650 billion/year</b> (World Bank 2023), exceeding foreign aid ($200B) by 3x and foreign direct investment ($400B) by 1.5x. Remittances are more <b>stable</b> than aid or FDI (they do not stop during recessions because migrants continue sending money home) and more <b>equitably distributed</b> (they go directly to families, not governments or corporations). The top recipient countries by % of GDP: <b>Tonga (44%)</b>, <b>Lebanon (38%)</b>, <b>Tajikistan (32%)</b>, <b>Nepal (25%)</b>. By absolute volume: <b>India ($125B)</b>, <b>Mexico ($63B)</b>, <b>China ($50B)</b>.") + s("Geographic Patterns: South-to-North Labor Flows") + p("The map reveals the geography of <b>international labor migration</b>. High-dependency countries cluster in: (1) <b>Pacific islands</b> (migration to Australia/NZ), (2) <b>Central America/Caribbean</b> (migration to US), (3) <b>Central/South Asia</b> (migration to Gulf states), (4) <b>Eastern Europe</b> (migration to Western EU). These corridors reflect wage differentials, colonial/linguistic ties, and geographic proximity. The spatial pattern partially compensates for the latitude-wealth gradient (Chart 23): wealth generated at high latitudes is transferred to low latitudes through migrant labor.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Reducing transfer costs</b> is the single most impactful policy intervention. The current average cost of sending $200 to Sub-Saharan Africa is 7.8% ($15.60 lost to fees). The SDG target is 3%. Achieving this would add <b>~$25 billion/year</b> to recipient family incomes, at zero cost to governments. This requires: regulatory reform of money transfer markets, digital payment infrastructure, and competition among remittance service providers. <b>Channeling remittances into productive investment</b> (rather than consumption) is the second priority: diaspora bond programmes (Ethiopia, India, Israel) allow migrants to invest in homeland infrastructure. Matching-grant schemes (for every $1 remitted into a savings or business account, the government adds $0.50) incentivize productive use.","w")

G["19"] = hd("Forest Cover","The lungs of the planet are in the tropics, and they are breathing harder every year.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>forest area as % of total land area</b>. The Amazon Basin (Brazil, Peru, Colombia) and Congo Basin (DRC, Republic of Congo, Cameroon, Gabon) dominate. Scandinavia and Southeast Asia also show high coverage. The Sahel, Middle East, and Central Asian steppes have minimal forest.") + s("Why Forests Matter: The Carbon Equation") + hl("Tropical forests contain approximately <b>250 billion tonnes of carbon</b> in their biomass and soil, roughly 30 years of current global CO2 emissions. They absorb ~2.5 billion tonnes of CO2 annually through photosynthesis. Deforestation releases this stored carbon, contributing approximately <b>10% of global greenhouse gas emissions</b>. The Amazon alone produces 20% of the world's oxygen and generates 'flying rivers' of atmospheric moisture that irrigate agriculture across South America. Loss of the Amazon would not only release massive carbon but would reduce rainfall across Brazil's agricultural heartland, threatening the world's largest soy and beef exporter.") + s("Spatial Paradox: Carbon vs. Poverty") + p("The world's most carbon-rich forests are in the world's <b>poorest countries</b>. DRC, with the second-largest tropical forest, has a GDP per capita of $1,500. This creates a spatial paradox: the countries least responsible for climate change are being asked to preserve the forests that benefit the entire planet. The <b>opportunity cost</b> of forest preservation (foregone agricultural and mining revenue) falls disproportionately on people in extreme poverty.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>REDD+</b> (Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and Forest Degradation) programmes pay countries and communities to preserve forest. Norway's $1 billion payment to Brazil for Amazon preservation (2008-2019) demonstrated proof of concept but collapsed when Brazil's political commitment waned under the Bolsonaro administration. <b>Carbon markets</b> can potentially scale forest payments: at $50/tonne CO2 (a reasonable social cost of carbon), preserving the Amazon's annual carbon absorption is worth ~$125 billion/year. Current payments are a tiny fraction of this. <b>Spatially targeted monitoring</b> using satellite imagery (Global Forest Watch, Planet Labs) now enables near-real-time deforestation detection at 30m resolution, making enforcement feasible.","w")

G["20"] = hd("Renewable Energy","A chart that looks green but hides a dirty secret.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>renewable energy as % of total final energy consumption</b>. <b>Darker = higher renewable share</b>. Sub-Saharan Africa shows the highest values (60-90%). Nordic countries show 50-70%.") + s("The Biomass Trap: Why High Percentages Can Be Bad") + hl("<b>Critical interpretation warning</b>: high renewable percentages in poor countries do NOT indicate solar panels and wind turbines. They reflect <b>traditional biomass dependence</b>: wood, charcoal, crop residues, and animal dung burned in open fires for cooking and heating. This biomass is technically 'renewable' (trees regrow) but causes: (1) <b>Deforestation</b> (charcoal demand is the leading driver of forest loss in East Africa), (2) <b>Indoor air pollution</b> (~2.6 million deaths/year, mostly women and children who inhale smoke from cooking fires), (3) <b>Time poverty</b> (women and children spend 1-4 hours/day collecting firewood, time that could be spent on education or income generation). <b>High renewable percentages in poor countries indicate energy poverty, not clean energy progress</b>.","w") + s("Modern Renewables: A Different Story") + p("In wealthy countries, high renewable shares reflect genuine clean energy investment: <b>Norway</b> (~70% from hydropower), <b>Denmark</b> (~55% from wind), <b>Iceland</b> (~85% from geothermal and hydro). These are modern, clean technologies that reduce carbon emissions without the health and environmental costs of biomass. The policy challenge is the <b>energy transition in the middle</b>: countries moving from biomass dependence to modern energy. The cleanest path is to leapfrog fossil fuels entirely (as some African countries are doing with solar), but coal and gas remain cheaper in most markets without carbon pricing.") + s("Policy") + hl("The correct metric for clean energy progress is not 'total renewable %' but <b>'modern renewable %'</b> (solar + wind + hydro + geothermal, excluding traditional biomass). Africa's clean energy transition requires: (1) <b>LPG for cooking</b> (replacing charcoal/wood), (2) <b>Grid-scale solar and wind</b> (Africa has the world's best solar irradiance and enormous wind resources), (3) <b>Battery storage and mini-grids</b> for off-grid communities. The cost of solar electricity has fallen 90% since 2010, making it now the cheapest source of new electricity generation in most of the world. Africa's solar potential is estimated at 10,000 GW, roughly 50x current global solar capacity.","g")

G["21"] = hd("Freshwater Stress","When withdrawal exceeds 100%, you are drinking your grandchildren's water.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Choropleth of <b>freshwater withdrawals as % of available renewable water resources</b>. <b>Values above 100% = unsustainable extraction</b>: the country is mining <em>fossil groundwater</em> that accumulated over millennia and does not replenish.") + s("The Science of Water Stress") + hl("Renewable water resources = precipitation that falls on a country's territory minus evapotranspiration, plus inflows from rivers originating elsewhere. <b>Withdrawal > 100%</b> means the country is extracting non-renewable aquifer water (analogous to spending savings rather than income). Saudi Arabia's Wadi As-Sirhan aquifer, one of the world's largest fossil water reserves, is projected to be depleted within 50 years at current withdrawal rates. India's Punjab aquifer, which sustains the Green Revolution's wheat production, is declining at 0.3-1.0 meters per year. When these aquifers are exhausted, there is no replacement at any price.") + s("The Arid Belt: 20-35 Degrees Latitude") + p("Water stress clusters in the <b>subtropical high-pressure belt</b> (20-35 degrees latitude in both hemispheres), where descending air in the Hadley Cell creates the world's great deserts: Sahara, Arabian, Thar, Sonoran, Kalahari, and Australian Outback. This is not a coincidence; it is atmospheric physics. Climate change is projected to <b>expand this belt poleward by 1-3 degrees latitude by 2100</b>, bringing Mediterranean climates into the arid zone and shifting the Sahel southward.") + s("Policy: Supply vs. Demand") + hl("<b>Demand-side interventions</b> (reducing consumption) are more sustainable than supply-side (increasing supply): (1) <b>Drip irrigation</b> reduces agricultural water use by 30-50% vs flood irrigation while increasing yields (Israel pioneered this; India and China are scaling it). (2) <b>Water pricing</b> that reflects true scarcity (most stressed countries subsidize water for agriculture, encouraging waste). (3) <b>Crop switching</b> from water-intensive crops (rice, sugarcane) to drought-tolerant alternatives in arid zones. <b>Supply-side</b>: (4) <b>Desalination</b> is viable for wealthy coastal nations but energy-intensive (5-10 kWh per m3) and produces brine waste. (5) <b>Wastewater recycling</b> (Israel recycles 85%, most countries <5%). (6) <b>Fog collection and atmospheric water generation</b> for remote arid communities.","w")

G["22"] = hd("Nations Bubble Map","Where humanity lives: a cartogram of the human presence on Earth.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Countries plotted at approximate capital-city coordinates as bubbles. <b>Size = total population</b>. Hover for GDP per capita and life expectancy. The map is dominated by the two largest bubbles: <b>India (~1.44 billion)</b> and <b>China (~1.41 billion)</b>, together representing 36% of humanity.") + s("The Spatial Distribution of Humanity") + hl("Humanity is <b>extraordinarily concentrated</b>. The Indo-Gangetic Plain (from Delhi to Dhaka) contains ~600 million people in an area the size of France. Java (Indonesia) houses 150 million people on an island smaller than England. The Nile Valley, the North China Plain, and the Rhine-Ruhr corridor are similarly dense. Meanwhile, <b>72% of Earth's land surface has fewer than 5 people per km2</b>. The Sahara, Siberia, Patagonia, the Amazon interior, Central Australia, and the Canadian Shield are effectively empty. This extreme spatial concentration means that <b>development interventions in a small number of geographic zones can affect billions of people</b>.") + s("Policy Implications") + hl("The population map has direct implications for infrastructure investment. <b>Climate adaptation</b>: the areas most densely populated (river deltas, coastal lowlands, monsoon zones) are also the most climate-vulnerable. Bangladesh (170M people, mostly in a delta <10m above sea level) and the Mekong Delta (18M people) face existential flooding risk. <b>Healthcare</b>: investing in primary health infrastructure in the Indo-Gangetic Plain (population density >1,000/km2) has the highest per-dollar population impact of any geographic investment on Earth. <b>Education</b>: similarly concentrated returns.","w")

# Continuing with geo-variable charts 23-36...
G["23"] = hd("Latitude-Wealth Gradient","Does where you were born determine what you will earn?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>X-axis: absolute latitude</b> (degrees from equator). <b>Y-axis: GDP per capita (PPP, log scale)</b>. Each dot = one country. <b>Color = continent</b>. A strong positive correlation: countries further from the equator tend to be wealthier.") + s("The Academic Debate: Geography vs. Institutions") + hl("This pattern is at the center of the most important debate in development economics. <b>The Geography Hypothesis</b> (Jeffrey Sachs, <em>Nature</em> 2001; Jared Diamond, <em>Guns, Germs, and Steel</em> 1997): tropical countries are poorer because of direct environmental constraints: higher disease burden (malaria costs Africa ~$12 billion/year in lost productivity), lower agricultural productivity (tropical soils are nutrient-poor; most of humanity's calorie crops were domesticated in temperate zones), and higher costs of infrastructure maintenance (tropical heat, humidity, and termites degrade buildings and roads faster). <b>The Institutions Hypothesis</b> (Acemoglu, Johnson, Robinson, <em>AER</em> 2001): European colonizers established <em>extractive institutions</em> in tropical regions (where they could not settle due to disease, so they set up plantations and mines) and <em>inclusive institutions</em> in temperate regions (where they settled permanently). The institutional legacy, not geography per se, determines wealth.","g") + s("The Exceptions That Prove the Rules") + p("<b>Singapore</b> (1 degree latitude, GDP >$130K): arguably the strongest evidence for the institutions hypothesis. Lee Kuan Yew's government transformed a tropical malarial swamp into the world's richest city-state through rule of law, education investment, and strategic trade policy. <b>Gulf States</b> (tropical, wealthy): resource endowments override geographic constraints when combined with small populations. <b>Botswana</b> (tropical, middle-income): diamond revenue managed through strong institutions. <b>Haiti vs. Dominican Republic</b>: same island, same latitude, vastly different wealth, pointing to institutional rather than geographic causation.") + s("Policy") + hl("If geography matters: tropical nations need <b>compensating investment</b> in healthcare (malaria elimination, tropical disease research), agricultural technology (heat-tolerant crop varieties, irrigation), and climate adaptation. If institutions matter: <b>governance reform, rule of law, property rights, and anti-corruption</b> are the priorities. The truth is likely both: geography creates initial conditions that institutions can either overcome (Singapore) or reinforce (many post-colonial African states). <b>The spatial pattern in this chart is not destiny</b>; it is a challenge that both geographic and institutional interventions can address.","w")

G["24"] = hd("Megacity Distance vs Life Expectancy","The farther you live from the global economic core, the shorter your life.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>X-axis: distance to nearest megacity</b> (>10 million population), computed using the <b>Haversine formula</b> (great-circle distance on Earth's surface) from each country's capital to the nearest of 20 reference megacities. <b>Y-axis: life expectancy</b>.") + s("The Connectivity Premium") + hl("Countries near megacities benefit from: (1) <b>Trade route proximity</b>: ports and airports near megacities offer cheaper freight and more frequent shipping. (2) <b>Medical supply chains</b>: pharmaceutical distribution networks radiate from megacities. (3) <b>Knowledge spillovers</b>: proximity to research hospitals, universities, and international organizations improves public health policy. (4) <b>Economic opportunity</b>: megacity labor markets attract workers from surrounding countries, generating remittance flows. The relationship is not merely correlation: the <b>mechanisms are genuinely spatial</b> (they operate through physical proximity and transportation networks).") + s("Remote Countries: The Double Penalty") + p("Pacific Island nations (Tuvalu, Kiribati, Samoa), landlocked African states (Chad, Central African Republic, Burundi), and Central Asian countries (Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan) are the most remote. They face higher costs for imported goods (including medicines), longer emergency evacuation times, fewer specialist medical visitors, and weaker integration into international health research networks.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Transportation infrastructure</b> (roads, ports, air connections) and <b>telemedicine</b> can reduce the isolation penalty. The WHO's <b>Hub-and-Spoke model</b> of healthcare delivery (tertiary hospitals in megacities connected to district hospitals via referral networks) explicitly addresses this geographic challenge. <b>Satellite-based internet</b> (Starlink and competitors) could dramatically reduce knowledge isolation for the most remote populations.","w")

G["25"] = hd("Climate Zones and Child Survival","The deadliest place for a child to be born is still where it has been for millennia: the tropics.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>Y-axis: under-5 mortality</b> (per 1,000 live births). <b>X-axis: absolute latitude</b>. <b>Color: climate zone</b> (Tropical 0-23.5 degrees, Subtropical 23.5-35, Temperate 35-55, Subarctic >55).") + s("Why the Tropics Kill Children") + hl("<b>Malaria</b> (~400,000 child deaths/year) is transmitted by <em>Anopheles</em> mosquitoes that thrive in warm, humid climates. It is essentially absent above 2,000m altitude or outside the tropical zone. <b>Diarrheal diseases</b> (~500,000 child deaths/year) are exacerbated by warm temperatures (which accelerate pathogen reproduction in contaminated water), lack of refrigeration (food spoils faster), and seasonal flooding (which overwhelms sanitation systems). <b>Nutritional deficiency</b>: tropical soils are often nutrient-poor (lateritic soils dominate, with low organic matter and rapid leaching). Crop yields per hectare are lower in the tropics for most staple crops. <b>Vector-borne diseases</b> beyond malaria (dengue, Zika, chikungunya, yellow fever) cluster in the tropical belt.") + s("The Subtropical Variance") + p("The <b>subtropical zone (23.5-35 degrees)</b> shows the most variance: some countries have very low mortality (Israel, Chile, Australia), others have high mortality (Yemen, Pakistan, parts of India). This variance demonstrates that in the subtropical transition zone, <b>governance and healthcare investment matter more than climate</b>. The same climate zone can produce radically different outcomes depending on institutional quality.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Climate-specific health interventions</b> can break the climate-mortality link: (1) <b>Insecticide-treated bed nets</b> for malaria zones ($5-7 per net, ~$30 per DALY saved). (2) <b>Oral rehydration salts + zinc</b> for diarrheal disease in hot climates ($0.50 per treatment). (3) <b>Cold-chain vaccination infrastructure</b> (solar-powered vaccine refrigerators for tropical areas without electricity). (4) <b>Water purification</b> (chlorine tablets, biosand filters) for communities without treated water. Rwanda and Bangladesh prove that even in the tropical zone, child mortality can be reduced to near-global-average levels through targeted public health investment.","w")

G["26"] = hd("The Cost of Conflict","War is the most expensive policy failure in human history.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Dual-panel scatter: <b>UCDP conflict intensity</b> (Uppsala Conflict Data Program, 0-10 scale) vs <b>GDP per capita</b> (left) and <b>life expectancy</b> (right).") + s("The UCDP Conflict Measure") + hl("The <b>Uppsala Conflict Data Program</b> (UCDP) is the gold standard for conflict measurement, maintained by Uppsala University since 1946. It codes all instances of organized armed violence involving at least one state actor and resulting in at least 25 battle-related deaths per year. The 0-10 intensity scale reflects both the frequency and lethality of violence. A score of 3-5 indicates ongoing but contained conflict (insurgency, separatist violence). A score of 7-10 indicates major war (Syria, Yemen, Ukraine).") + s("The Devastating Cost") + p("Even <b>moderate conflict (intensity 3-5)</b> is associated with 10-15 years lower life expectancy and GDP per capita reductions of 50-80% compared to peaceful neighbors. The mechanisms: (1) <b>Physical destruction</b> of hospitals, schools, roads, bridges, power plants. (2) <b>Population displacement</b> (105 million forcibly displaced people globally, the highest number ever recorded). (3) <b>Diversion of government spending</b> from development to military. (4) <b>Agricultural disruption</b> (farmers flee fields, food production collapses). (5) <b>Psychological trauma</b> (PTSD, depression, substance abuse) that reduces human capital for decades. (6) <b>Brain drain</b> (the most educated and skilled emigrate first).") + s("Policy") + hl("The World Bank (2018) estimates that every <b>$1 spent on conflict prevention</b> saves <b>$10-16 in post-conflict reconstruction</b>. Peacekeeping missions, despite their costs and imperfections, are among the highest-return investments in global development. <b>Spatial analysis</b> is increasingly used for conflict early warning: satellite imagery detects troop movements and displacement; mobile phone data reveals social network fragmentation preceding violence; crop failure mapping identifies food insecurity (a common conflict trigger). The geographic concentration of conflict in the Sahel, Horn of Africa, Middle East, and parts of South/Southeast Asia suggests that <b>regional rather than global approaches</b> to conflict prevention may be most effective.","w")

G["27"] = hd("The Sea Access Premium","Being landlocked is not just inconvenient. It is a systematic economic curse.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Box plots comparing <b>GDP per capita distributions</b> for landlocked vs coastal countries, faceted by continent.") + s("The Landlocked Penalty") + hl("<b>Landlocked countries</b> face: (1) <b>Higher transport costs</b>: 15-20% of export value vs 5-8% for coastal nations, because goods must cross at least one international border (with attendant customs delays, tariffs, and corruption) before reaching a port. (2) <b>Dependence on transit neighbors</b>: if the transit country experiences political instability, conflict, or hostile relations, the landlocked country's trade can be severed entirely (as happened to Ethiopia when Eritrea closed its border, or to Zimbabwe during Mozambique's civil war). (3) <b>Reduced FDI</b>: multinational corporations prefer coastal locations with port access for manufacturing and distribution. (4) <b>Agricultural export constraints</b>: perishable goods (fruit, flowers, fresh fish) lose value during the longer transport times.") + s("The Africa Penalty") + p("The penalty is <b>largest in Africa</b>, where 16 landlocked nations face the worst roads, most border crossings, most corrupt customs regimes, and most politically unstable transit neighbors. <b>Uganda</b> must route exports through either Kenya (1,400 km to Mombasa port) or Tanzania (1,200 km to Dar es Salaam). <b>Chad</b> is 1,500+ km from the nearest port. In Europe, by contrast, landlocked countries (Austria, Switzerland, Czech Republic) compensate through EU integration, excellent rail networks, and stable transit agreements.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Regional transit agreements</b> (the African Continental Free Trade Area, AfCFTA, launched 2021), <b>railway investment</b> (especially North-South corridors in East Africa), <b>customs harmonization</b> (one-stop border posts reducing crossing times from days to hours), and <b>dry port development</b> (inland logistics hubs with customs clearance capacity). <b>Botswana is the exemplary exception</b>: landlocked but well-governed, it leveraged diamond revenue into education, healthcare, and infrastructure, achieving middle-income status despite geographic disadvantage. This proves that the landlocked penalty, while severe, is not deterministic.","w")

# Charts 28-36: shorter but still deep
G["28"] = hd("The Digital-Geographic Divide","Two divides layered: latitude and income, both predicting who is online.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Internet usage (%) vs absolute latitude, <b>colored by World Bank income group</b> (Low, Lower-Middle, Upper-Middle, High).") + s("Disentangling Geography and Wealth") + hl("Income group explains most variance: at any latitude, higher-income countries have higher internet penetration. But latitude adds <b>independent explanatory power</b>: even within the same income group, higher-latitude countries have slightly higher penetration. This residual effect may reflect: (1) historical diffusion patterns (the internet originated at high latitudes), (2) infrastructure density (temperate countries tend to have denser road/power/telecom networks), (3) institutional quality (which correlates with latitude due to colonial history, per Acemoglu et al. 2001). <b>Policy</b>: universal broadband programmes should target the intersection of <em>low latitude</em> and <em>low income</em> for maximum impact. The UN Broadband Commission's affordability target (<2% of monthly income) requires specific attention to tropical low-income countries.","g")

G["29"] = hd("Fertility by Climate Zone","Climate does not determine fertility, but it shapes the landscape on which demographic choices are made.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Violin plots of fertility distributions across four climate zones. <b>Violin width = density of countries</b> at that fertility level (wider = more countries). <b>Tropical</b>: widest spread (1.5 to 7.0), highest median (~4.0). <b>Temperate</b>: tight clustering at 1.2-1.8 (completed transition).") + s("Climate as Context, Not Cause") + hl("Climate does NOT directly cause high fertility. Rather, the tropics contain countries at vastly different stages of the demographic transition due to differences in <b>women's education</b> (the single strongest predictor of fertility), <b>contraceptive access</b>, <b>urbanization rates</b>, and <b>governance quality</b>. Costa Rica (tropical, fertility 1.3) and Mauritius (tropical, 1.4) prove that tropical location does not prevent low fertility. Niger (tropical, 6.8) and Chad (tropical, 6.1) show that the combination of low female education, high child mortality, and rural subsistence agriculture maintains high fertility regardless of policy rhetoric. <b>The within-tropical variance is the key insight</b>: it shows where policy intervention is possible and where it has succeeded.","g") + s("Policy") + hl("Interventions targeting high-fertility tropical countries: (1) Girls' secondary education (each year reduces fertility by 0.3-0.5 births). (2) Community-based contraceptive distribution (reducing unmet need from 25% to <10%). (3) Child survival programmes (when parents are confident children survive, they have fewer). (4) Social protection programmes that reduce the economic incentive for large families. All of these can be implemented regardless of climate zone.","w")

G["30"] = hd("Urbanization vs Renewable Energy","A chart that rewards careful reading and punishes lazy interpretation.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Scatter of <b>urban population %</b> (X) vs <b>renewable energy share</b> (Y). The relationship is <b>counterintuitively negative</b>: more urbanized countries tend to have LOWER renewable percentages.") + s("Why the Negative Relationship Is Misleading") + hl("This is a <b>definitional artifact</b>. Urban energy consumption is dominated by fossil-fuel-generated grid electricity, gasoline, and natural gas. Rural energy in developing countries is dominated by <b>traditional biomass</b> (wood, charcoal), which is classified as 'renewable' in this dataset. So the negative slope does NOT mean cities are bad for clean energy. It means the definition of 'renewable' conflates dirty biomass with clean solar/wind. <b>If you filter to modern renewables only</b> (solar + wind + hydro + geothermal, excluding biomass), the relationship in wealthy countries is actually <em>positive</em>: urbanization enables grid-scale renewable deployment.","w") + s("Policy") + p("Urban clean energy transitions require: <b>grid-scale solar and wind</b> (not biomass), <b>building energy efficiency standards</b>, <b>electric public transit</b>, and <b>district heating/cooling systems</b>. The correct metric for tracking clean energy progress is <em>modern renewable %</em>, not total renewable %.")

G["31"] = hd("The Arid Belt","Between 20 and 35 degrees latitude, the atmosphere conspires to deny water to millions.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Freshwater withdrawals (% of renewable resources) vs absolute latitude. The <b>20-35 degree band</b> shows dramatic stress clustering.") + s("Atmospheric Physics: Why This Belt Exists") + hl("The subtropical arid belt is created by the <b>Hadley Cell</b>: warm air rises at the equator (creating tropical rainforest), moves poleward at high altitude, and <b>descends at 20-35 degrees latitude</b>. Descending air warms and dries, creating high-pressure zones with minimal rainfall. This is why the world's great deserts (Sahara, Arabian, Thar, Sonoran, Kalahari, Australian Outback) all lie in this band. <b>Climate change is expanding this belt poleward</b> at ~0.5 degrees per decade, meaning the Sahara is moving south into the Sahel, and Mediterranean climates are becoming more arid. By 2100, the band could extend to 22-38 degrees.","g") + s("Policy") + hl("Agricultural water efficiency is the biggest lever: <b>drip irrigation</b> (30-50% water savings), <b>deficit irrigation</b> (providing less water than maximum demand at non-critical growth stages), <b>mulching</b> (reducing evaporation), and <b>crop switching</b> (from water-intensive rice/sugarcane to drought-tolerant millets/sorghum). <b>Water pricing</b> is essential: most arid-belt countries subsidize agricultural water, encouraging overuse. Israel's water management (desalination + drip irrigation + 85% wastewater recycling) demonstrates that technology can overcome natural scarcity, but requires governance capacity and capital investment.","w")

G["32"] = hd("Healthcare by Latitude","The global doctor drought follows the equator.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Physicians per 1,000 population vs absolute latitude. <b>Strong positive correlation</b>: fewer doctors near the equator.") + s("Three Mechanisms") + hl("<b>(1) Brain drain</b>: approximately 25% of physicians trained in Sub-Saharan Africa practice in OECD countries. The WHO estimates that Africa has 3% of the world's health workers but 25% of its disease burden. (2) <b>Training capacity gaps</b>: medical school capacity in tropical developing countries produces fewer graduates per capita. Uganda has one medical school per 10 million people; the UK has one per 3 million. (3) <b>Income effects</b>: wealthier countries (higher latitudes) can afford more physicians per capita and offer salaries that attract and retain doctors.") + s("Outliers") + p("<b>Cuba</b> (near equator, >8 physicians/1,000): the most striking exception. Cuba's centralized healthcare system, despite severe economic constraints, trained massive numbers of doctors and exports medical professionals worldwide. It proves that <b>policy choice can override geography and wealth</b>. <b>Former Soviet states</b> (Georgia, Moldova, Tajikistan) show high physician density at moderate latitudes, reflecting historical centralized training systems.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Community health workers</b> (CHWs): training local residents to provide basic preventive and curative care. Ethiopia's Health Extension Programme (38,000 CHWs) reduced child mortality by 30%. <b>Telemedicine</b>: connecting rural patients to urban specialists via mobile phone. <b>Task-shifting</b>: training nurses and clinical officers to perform procedures traditionally reserved for doctors. <b>Retention incentives</b>: rural service bonuses, housing, and career advancement tracks to keep doctors in underserved areas.","w")

G["33"] = hd("Education vs Connectivity","Remote countries, remote futures: how geography shapes schooling.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Primary school completion rate vs distance to nearest megacity (>10M population).") + s("Mechanisms") + hl("Remote countries have lower school completion because: (1) <b>Teacher recruitment</b>: qualified teachers prefer urban postings. Remote schools face chronic vacancies. (2) <b>Supply chains</b>: textbooks, examination materials, and school equipment must travel further. (3) <b>Infrastructure</b>: remote schools are more likely to lack electricity, internet, and safe buildings. (4) <b>Opportunity costs</b>: in subsistence agricultural economies (common in remote areas), children's labor is economically valuable, pulling them out of school during planting and harvest.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Distance learning</b> (mobile-first, low-bandwidth platforms like Kolibri) can partially compensate. <b>Teacher incentive structures</b>: hardship allowances, housing provision, and accelerated promotion for remote postings. <b>BRAC's model</b> (Bangladesh): one-room schools with locally recruited teachers, proven to raise completion rates by 15-25 percentage points in the most remote communities. <b>Satellite-based internet</b> could transform educational access in the most isolated areas.","w")

G["34"] = hd("Trade Across the East-West Axis","The two great trade blocs of the 21st century, visible in a single scatter plot.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Trade openness (exports+imports as % of GDP) vs longitude. <b>Two clear peaks</b>: 0-30E (European trade zone) and 100-120E (East Asian export economies).") + s("The Two Blocs") + hl("<b>Peak 1 (0-30E)</b>: the European Union's single market, the most integrated trade bloc in history. Member states eliminated internal tariffs, harmonized regulations, and created a common currency, enabling massive intra-bloc trade. <b>Peak 2 (100-120E)</b>: the East Asian supply chain network, centered on China, Japan, South Korea, Taiwan, and ASEAN. Manufactured goods flow between these countries in complex, multi-stage production chains (e.g., a smartphone: designed in the US, chipset from Taiwan, screen from South Korea, assembled in China, shipped from Vietnam). <b>The trough (30-90E)</b>: Middle East, Central Asia, and South Asia, less integrated into either bloc.") + s("Policy") + hl("Countries in the trough can leverage their <b>geographic position as trade corridors</b>. China's Belt and Road Initiative targets exactly this logic: connecting the two peaks through Central Asian railways, Middle Eastern ports, and South Asian highways. <b>Turkey</b> and <b>UAE</b> are already positioning themselves as trade bridge economies. The African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA) could create a third peak around 20-30E if implementation succeeds.","w")

G["35"] = hd("Forest Cover and Maternal Health","High forest cover can kill mothers. Not because forests are dangerous, but because remoteness is.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Maternal mortality ratio (deaths per 100,000 live births) vs forest cover (% of land area).") + s("The Remoteness Mechanism") + hl("Countries with very high forest cover (Congo Basin, Amazon) show high maternal mortality. The mechanism is <b>not that forests are unhealthy</b> but that dense forest cover correlates with: (1) <b>Road inaccessibility</b>: forest roads are often unpaved, seasonal, and impassable during rains. (2) <b>Long distances to emergency obstetric care</b>: the 'three delays' model of maternal mortality (delay in deciding to seek care, delay in reaching facility, delay in receiving treatment) is dominated by the second delay in forested areas. (3) <b>Low population density</b>: it is not economically feasible to place a hospital with surgical capacity in every forest community.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Skilled birth attendants</b> in community health posts (not just hospitals). <b>Emergency referral transport</b>: motorcycle ambulances designed for forest paths (the eRanger model deployed in Malawi). <b>Telemedicine-guided delivery support</b>: midwives connected via mobile phone to obstetricians who can guide management of complications. <b>Maternity waiting homes</b>: accommodations near hospitals where women from remote areas can stay in the final weeks of pregnancy. These interventions directly address the spatial barrier without requiring the impossible (building hospitals in every forest village).","w")

G["36"] = hd("Remittance Dependency by Geography","The invisible subsidy flowing from high latitudes to low, one migrant worker at a time.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Remittances (% of GDP) vs absolute latitude. <b>Negative correlation</b>: closer to the equator = higher remittance dependency.") + s("Geography of Labor Migration") + hl("The pattern reflects <b>South-to-North labor migration</b>: workers from low-latitude developing countries migrate to high-latitude wealthy countries and send money home. The major corridors: <b>Mexico/Central America to US</b>, <b>Philippines to Gulf/US/Europe</b>, <b>South Asia to Gulf states</b>, <b>North Africa to EU</b>, <b>Eastern Europe to Western EU</b>, <b>Pacific Islands to Australia/NZ</b>. Each corridor reflects a combination of wage differentials, colonial/linguistic ties, geographic proximity, and visa regimes.") + s("Remittances as Informal Redistribution") + p("Remittance flows partially <b>compensate for the latitude-wealth gradient</b> (Chart 23). Wealth generated at high latitudes is transferred to low latitudes through migrant labor, creating a parallel 'informal' redistribution system alongside official development aid. Unlike aid, remittances go directly to families (not governments), are spent on locally identified priorities (education, healthcare, housing), and are remarkably resilient during economic downturns (migrants continue sending money even when their own incomes fall).") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Reducing transfer costs</b> from 6-7% to the SDG target of 3% would add ~$25 billion/year to recipient families. This requires: digital payment infrastructure, competition among remittance providers, and regulatory reform. <b>Productive channeling</b>: diaspora bonds (letting migrants invest in homeland infrastructure), matching grants for business investment, and financial literacy programmes to move remittance use from consumption to asset-building.","w")

# ===== CHARTS 38-64: INDIA ELECTIONS, 3D, ANIMATED =====

G["38"] = hd("Constituency Area vs Electoral Outcomes","India's largest constituencies are also its most democratically disadvantaged.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Dual scatter: <b>constituency area (log km2, X)</b> vs <b>turnout (Y, left panel)</b> and <b>victory margin (Y, right panel)</b>. Color = alliance.") + s("Why Log Scale?") + hl("Constituency area spans <b>4 orders of magnitude</b>: from 29 km2 (Chandni Chowk, Delhi) to 173,266 km2 (Ladakh). On a linear scale, all urban constituencies would be invisible at the origin. The <b>log transformation</b> <code>log10(area)</code> compresses this range so that both extremes are visible and the relationship can be assessed visually.") + s("The Size-Turnout Relationship") + p("A <b>negative slope</b>: larger constituencies have systematically lower turnout. This is not surprising: voters in Ladakh (173K km2, population density <1/km2) face far greater logistical barriers than voters in urban Delhi (area 100 km2, density 11,000/km2). The mechanisms: (1) greater travel distance to polling stations, (2) sparser campaign infrastructure, (3) higher cost of political information (fewer media outlets, less party presence). Area itself is <b>spatially autocorrelated</b> (Moran's I = 0.16, p < 0.001): large constituencies cluster together in Rajasthan, MP, and NE India, creating geographic zones of systematic underrepresentation.") + s("Policy") + hl("The Election Commission should deploy <b>more polling stations per voter</b> in large-area constituencies. The current uniform norm (~1 station per 1,200-1,500 voters) fails to account for geographic dispersal. A voter walking 15 km to a polling station in Ladakh faces a fundamentally different barrier than a voter walking 500 meters in Delhi. <b>Mobile polling units</b>, <b>expanded postal voting</b>, and <b>multi-day polling</b> (spreading the election over 2-3 days in large constituencies to allow travel) would directly address the area-turnout penalty.","w")

G["39"] = hd("Moran's I Scatterplot","The fundamental diagnostic tool of spatial statistics, applied to Indian democracy.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Dual panel. <b>X-axis</b> = standardized value (how many standard deviations a constituency is from the national mean). <b>Y-axis</b> = spatial lag (the weighted average of neighbors' standardized values, using KNN k=8 row-standardized weights). <b>Gold regression line: slope = Moran's I.</b>") + s("Reading the Four Quadrants") + hl("<b>HH (top-right)</b>: High value surrounded by high neighbors = <em>Hot Spot</em> (spatial clustering of high values). <b>LL (bottom-left)</b>: Low surrounded by low = <em>Cold Spot</em>. <b>HL (bottom-right)</b>: High surrounded by low = <em>positive outlier</em> (local factor overriding regional trend). <b>LH (top-left)</b>: Low surrounded by high = <em>negative outlier</em>. Points far from the origin in HH/LL quadrants are the most strongly clustered. Points in HL/LH are analytically the most interesting: they identify constituencies where <b>local factors</b> (a charismatic candidate, a local caste dynamic, a particularly effective party organization) override the regional baseline.") + s("What the Slopes Tell Us") + p("<b>Turnout: I = 0.64</b>. Slope is steep. Most points in HH (southern hot spots) and LL (Hindi belt cold spots). This means voter turnout is <b>strongly geographically determined</b>: knowing where a constituency is tells you a lot about its turnout. <b>Margin: I = 0.26</b>. Shallower slope. More scatter in HL/LH quadrants. Electoral competitiveness is less spatially structured: safe and competitive seats are more geographically mixed.") + s("Policy Implications") + hl("The steep turnout slope means that <b>area-based interventions</b> (targeting clusters rather than individual constituencies) may be most efficient for voter mobilization. The shallower margin slope means that <b>individual-constituency strategies</b> (candidate selection, campaign tactics) matter more for competitiveness than geographic location. <b>HL outliers</b> (high-turnout constituencies in low-turnout regions) should be studied as positive deviance cases: what are they doing differently?","w")

G["40"] = hd("Turnout Swing 2019 to 2024","The geography of democratic disengagement.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Map of turnout change between 2019 and 2024. <b>Red = turnout dropped</b>. <b>Blue = turnout rose</b>. <b>Size = magnitude</b>. National average: <b>-1.4 percentage points</b>.") + s("Interpreting Swings") + hl("<b>Negative swing</b> = fewer people voted. Possible causes: voter fatigue (same candidates/parties as before), anti-incumbency apathy (dislike all options equally), logistical barriers (heat waves, flooding, security concerns), or deliberate abstention as protest. <b>Positive swing</b> = mobilization succeeded. Possible drivers: new voters entering (demographic turnover), effective party mobilization campaigns, competitive races generating excitement, or specific local issues galvanizing participation.") + s("Spatial Clustering of Disengagement") + p("Red clusters are visible in parts of UP (possible voter fatigue in BJP strongholds), Gujarat (similar), and Rajasthan (possible anti-incumbency after state government change). Blue clusters in West Bengal (competitive mobilization), Assam (NRC-related politicization), and parts of Tamil Nadu (competitive INDIA vs NDA races). <b>The clustering is not random</b>: it follows state-level and regional political dynamics.") + s("Policy") + hl("The ECI should conduct <b>post-election surveys in high-negative-swing constituencies</b> to diagnose causes. Were swings driven by weather/logistics (addressable with more polling stations), security concerns (addressable with deployment), or genuine disaffection (requiring political competition reform)? <b>SVEEP</b> (Systematic Voters' Education and Electoral Participation) should be spatially targeted at red zones with the largest negative swings.","w")

G["41"] = hd("Center vs Periphery","Does distance from Delhi predict electoral outcomes?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Victory margin vs <b>distance from Delhi in degrees</b> (Euclidean distance in geographic coordinates from each constituency centroid to Delhi). Color = alliance. Size = electorate.") + s("Rokkan's Core-Periphery Model") + hl("Stein Rokkan (1970) theorized that national political systems are structured by a <b>core-periphery cleavage</b>: the political center (capital, economic hub) exerts systematic influence on peripheral regions through administrative control, cultural dominance, and economic dependency. In the Indian context: does proximity to Delhi (the seat of central government, major media, national party headquarters) systematically shape electoral outcomes?") + s("Finding: No Strong Linear Effect") + p("The scatter shows <b>no strong linear relationship</b> between distance from Delhi and margin. However, <b>variance changes</b>: near Delhi, margins range widely (some very safe NDA seats, some fiercely competitive). Far from Delhi (>15 degrees, covering south and northeast), margins are more uniformly distributed. <b>Alliance coloring</b> reveals that NDA dominates near Delhi while INDIA is more prevalent at greater distances.") + s("Interpretation") + hl("The lack of a strong distance-decay effect is <b>positive news for Indian democracy</b>: it means national politics is not simply radiating from a Delhi bubble. Multiple regional centers of political power (Chennai, Kolkata, Mumbai, Patna) maintain autonomous political cultures. However, the NDA-near, INDIA-far pattern is consistent with a <b>cultural-geographic divide</b> between the Hindi heartland (which surrounds Delhi) and linguistic minority regions (which are distant from it).","g")

G["42"] = hd("Political Cylinder (3D)","India's political geography, unrolled onto a navigable 3D surface.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("543 constituencies mapped onto a rotating 3D cylinder. <b>Height = latitude</b> (south at bottom, north at top). <b>Angular position = longitude</b>. <b>Color = winning alliance</b> (saffron = NDA, blue = INDIA, grey = others). <b>Pink octahedra = women winners</b>. Drag to rotate. Scroll to zoom.") + s("Why a Cylinder?") + hl("The <b>cylindrical equidistant projection</b> preserves the North-South ordering (vertical axis) while wrapping the East-West dimension (angular). This is useful for India because the primary political divide is <b>latitudinal</b> (North-South), not longitudinal. On the cylinder, the divide appears as a <b>horizontal color boundary</b>: blue (INDIA) dominates the lower half (south), saffron (NDA) dominates the upper half (north), and the transition zone (Maharashtra, Telangana, Karnataka) wraps around the middle.") + s("What Women Winners Reveal") + p("<b>Pink octahedra are sparse</b> (~47 out of 543 nodes, 8.7%). They are scattered without clear geographic concentration, consistent with the weak Moran's I for women winners (0.06, Chart 54). This visual sparsity makes the case for the Women's Reservation Bill more powerfully than any number.") + s("Interacting with the Cylinder") + p("Drag horizontally to rotate and see how the political divide wraps around India's geography. Hover any node for constituency details (name, state, winner, party, margin, turnout). The cylinder reveals patterns that flat maps obscure: for example, the <b>northeastern region</b> (which is geographically small but electorally distinct) appears as a cluster of nodes at the far right of the cylinder's mid-height, making its mixed political character visible.")

G["43"] = hd("Development Globe (3D)","What does global development look like from space?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("196 countries on a rotating 3D sphere, with bars extruding outward proportional to the selected metric. <b>Three switchable metrics</b> via buttons at the top: GDP per capita, life expectancy, fertility rate. <b>Color = continent</b>. Drag to rotate.") + s("Three Different Worlds") + hl("<b>GDP mode</b>: the Northern Hemisphere towers over the South. North America, Europe, and East Asia show tall bars. Sub-Saharan Africa and South/Southeast Asia show short bars. The visual is dramatic: it looks like the Northern Hemisphere is wearing a crown of wealth. <b>Fertility mode</b>: the pattern <em>inverts</em>. Africa towers, Europe shrinks. The tallest bars are in Niger, Chad, Mali, DRC. <b>Life expectancy mode</b>: a compromise between the two. The globe appears more uniform, reflecting the fact that health convergence (Chart 53) has partially equalized life expectancy even where wealth diverges.") + s("Policy Insight") + hl("The globe perspective reveals that development challenges are <b>hemispherically clustered</b>: virtually all low-GDP, high-fertility, low-lifeExp countries occupy a tropical belt between 23.5N and 23.5S latitude. This geographic concentration means that international development cooperation, climate adaptation funding, and health infrastructure investment can be <b>spatially targeted</b> with high efficiency. A single programme covering the tropical belt would reach the vast majority of the world's development challenges.","g")

G["44"] = hd("The Double Helix of Indian Democracy","India's political DNA: two intertwined strands of identity spiraling through geographic space.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("NDA (saffron) and INDIA (blue) alliance constituencies spiral upward in two DNA-like helices. <b>South at bottom, north at top</b>. <b>Node size = victory margin</b> (large = safe seat). <b>Tube backbones</b> trace each alliance's geographic path.") + s("The Metaphor") + hl("The double helix is not merely decorative. It encodes a structural insight: India's two major political formations are <b>geographically complementary</b>, occupying largely non-overlapping spatial niches (NDA in the north, INDIA in the south and east). They <b>interweave</b> in swing states (Maharashtra, Karnataka, Rajasthan), where the two strands cross. The helix structure suggests that India's political divide is not a clean geographic line but a <b>helical intertwining</b>: both formations are present everywhere, but their relative dominance rotates as you move along the latitude axis.") + s("What the Node Sizes Reveal") + p("Large saffron nodes (safe NDA seats) concentrate in the upper turns (Hindi belt). Large blue nodes (safe INDIA seats) concentrate in the lower turns (south, Bengal). <b>Small nodes</b> (competitive seats with thin margins) cluster in the <b>middle turns</b> (the Maharashtra-Karnataka-Telangana belt), which is the geographic battleground for national power.") + s("Policy") + hl("Any party seeking to form a government must win the middle turns of the helix. This spatial analysis suggests that campaign resources should be concentrated in the <b>geographic transition zone</b> (~15-20 degrees latitude) rather than in the safe strongholds at the extremes.","w")

G["45"] = hd("Continental Development Space (3D)","Three dimensions of development, no information loss.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("196 countries in 3D space. <b>X = GDP per capita (log)</b>. <b>Y = Life Expectancy</b>. <b>Z = Fertility Rate</b>. <b>Bubble size = population</b>. <b>Color = continent</b>. Click-drag to rotate.") + s("What 3D Reveals That 2D Cannot") + hl("In any 2D projection (GDP vs lifeExp, GDP vs fertility, lifeExp vs fertility), one dimension is lost. The 3D scatter preserves all three simultaneously. This reveals <b>outlier countries</b> that appear normal in 2D but are anomalous in 3D: (1) <b>Gulf states</b>: high GDP (far right), moderate lifeExp (mid-height), low fertility (low Z). They occupy a unique position: wealthy but with health outcomes below what their wealth predicts, possibly due to lifestyle diseases and healthcare quality issues. (2) <b>Cuba</b>: low GDP (far left), HIGH lifeExp (high Y), low fertility. It occupies the opposite anomaly: poor but healthy, due to prioritized healthcare investment. (3) <b>Sub-Saharan Africa</b>: forms a <em>distinct cluster</em> in the high-Z, low-X, low-Y octant. No other continent occupies this space.") + s("Policy") + hl("The continental clustering suggests that <b>continent-specific development strategies</b> are appropriate: Africa's cluster (high fertility, low GDP, low lifeExp) requires simultaneous investment in health, education, and economic growth. Asia's wide spread (from Afghanistan to Singapore) suggests heterogeneous, country-specific approaches. Europe's tight cluster (low fertility, high GDP, high lifeExp) focuses on aging and immigration policy.","g")

G["46"] = hd("Women + Area Hypothesis","Do women win in different kinds of constituencies than men?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Three panels: (1) <b>Box + strip plots</b> of constituency area by winner gender. (2) <b>Population density vs margin</b> with women highlighted as pink diamonds. (3) <b>Category breakdown</b> (GEN/SC/ST).") + s("The Statistical Test") + hl("<b>Mann-Whitney U test</b>: a non-parametric test comparing two independent samples. It does not assume normal distributions (important because constituency area is heavily right-skewed). The test ranks ALL observations from both groups together, then tests whether one group's ranks are systematically higher. <b>Result</b>: women winners have significantly <b>smaller</b> constituencies (median 3,324 km2 vs men 4,073 km2). The p-value < 0.05 means there is less than a 5% probability that this difference occurred by chance.") + s("Interpretation") + p("Women are more likely to win in <b>smaller, denser (more urban) constituencies</b>. Mechanisms: (1) Better media access in urban areas (women's campaigns may benefit more from media coverage than physical rallies). (2) More educated electorates (research shows educated voters are more willing to vote for women). (3) Party calculations (parties nominate women where they believe gender is an electoral advantage). (4) Shorter campaign distances (reducing the mobility constraint that affects women candidates). <b>SC reserved seats</b> show 15.5% women representation (highest of any category), possibly because the reservation disrupts normal male-dominated selection.") + s("Policy") + hl("Parties considering women candidates should factor in <b>constituency geography</b>: smaller, denser, more urban seats offer better electoral environments for women. But this also means that <b>without the Women's Reservation Bill</b>, women will remain confined to a geographically narrow niche (urban, small, educated constituencies), unable to break into the large rural seats that dominate Indian politics.","w")

G["47"] = hd("3D Spatial Histogram","Quantitative data superimposed on geographic space: the concept of the spatial histogram.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("3D bars rising from constituency centroid locations over the India map. <b>Height = selected metric</b> (electorate ratio, turnout, or margin), switchable with buttons. <b>Color = winning alliance</b>.") + s("What Each Metric Reveals") + hl("<b>Electorate ratio mode</b>: northern bars tower (UP/Bihar constituencies have 2x the national average electorate) while southern bars are shorter. This directly visualizes the <b>delimitation inequality</b>: northern votes are worth less because constituencies are overpopulated. <b>Turnout mode</b>: the pattern <em>inverts</em>. Southern bars are taller (higher turnout). The geographic anti-correlation between electorate size and turnout is visible: the most overpopulated constituencies also have the lowest turnout, compounding the democratic deficit. <b>Margin mode</b>: bars are more evenly distributed, reflecting the moderate spatial clustering of competitiveness.") + s("Policy") + hl("The 3D histogram makes the case for delimitation reform more <b>viscerally</b> than any 2D chart. When viewed from a low angle, the towering northern bars literally represent voters whose democratic voice is diluted. The combination of high electorate ratio AND low turnout in the Hindi belt means that these constituencies are doubly underrepresented: fewer people vote, and each vote counts for less.","w")

G["48"] = hd("Alliance LISA + Women Bivariate","The spatial structure of India's political divide, and its non-relationship with women's representation.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>Left panel</b>: LISA clusters on a binary NDA (+1) / INDIA (-1) coding. <b>Right panel</b>: state-level bubble chart of NDA seat share vs women's representation.") + s("The Alliance LISA") + hl("<b>Moran's I = 0.37</b> (strong clustering). NDA coded as +1, INDIA as -1. <b>110 NDA strongholds</b> (orange, p < 0.05): constituencies where NDA won AND neighbors won NDA. Concentrated in UP, Bihar, MP, Gujarat. <b>112 INDIA strongholds</b> (blue): concentrated in Kerala, TN, Bengal, Punjab. <b>Spatial outliers</b> (HL/LH): NDA wins in INDIA strongholds or vice versa, often reflecting local candidate effects or minority community voting patterns.") + s("The Non-Correlation with Women") + p("Right panel: NDA seat share (X) vs women elected as % of seats (Y), by state. <b>No significant correlation</b>. States with high NDA dominance (UP, Gujarat) have poor women's representation. States with high INDIA dominance (Kerala, Bengal) have equally poor women's representation. <b>This demolishes any argument that one alliance is inherently better for women's political inclusion.</b>") + s("Policy") + hl("The Women's Reservation Bill must be implemented as a <b>non-partisan structural mandate</b> because neither alliance's voluntary behavior has produced adequate representation. The 33% reservation target line in the right panel shows how far <em>every single state</em> falls short, regardless of which alliance dominates it.","w")

# ANIMATED CHARTS 49-58
G["49"] = hd("GDP Bar Chart Race","Thirty years of economic competition, compressed into 30 seconds.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Top 15 nations by GDP per capita (PPP) racing from 1992 to 2022. <b>Press play</b> to watch countries overtake each other in real time. <b>Color = continent</b>.") + s("The Stories in the Race") + hl("<b>Ireland's surge</b> (from mid-table to top 3) reflects its role as a <em>corporate tax haven</em>: multinational profits (Apple, Google, Pfizer) are booked in Ireland, inflating GDP far above actual resident welfare. Ireland's GDP is ~2x its GNI (Gross National Income). <b>Qatar</b>: resource wealth (natural gas) concentrated in a tiny citizen population (300K citizens; 2.5M total residents, mostly non-citizen workers excluded from per-capita calculations). <b>Singapore</b>: genuine productivity-driven growth in a city-state through education, trade, and governance. <b>Norway</b>: oil wealth managed through a sovereign wealth fund ($1.4 trillion, the world's largest) that preserves wealth for future generations. <b>The US</b>: a steady top-5 presence, but its ranking masks extreme within-country inequality (median household income would rank lower).") + s("Policy Caveat") + hl("<b>Per-capita GDP rankings can be deeply misleading</b>. Ireland's GDP overstates resident welfare. Qatar's excludes most residents. The US average hides extreme inequality. <b>Median household income</b> or <b>GDP per capita adjusted for inequality</b> (which the UNDP publishes as 'inequality-adjusted HDI') gives a more accurate picture of typical lived experience.","g")

G["50"] = hd("Electoral Swing: 2019 vs 2024","Two elections, one animation, 214 party changes.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated geo scatter toggling between the 2019 and 2024 elections. Bubbles represent constituencies at their geographic locations. <b>Bubble size = victory margin</b>. <b>Color = winning alliance</b>. The 1.5-second transition animation morphs bubbles as margins shift and alliances change.") + s("Key Swings") + hl("NDA lost significant ground in: <b>UP</b> (Samajwadi Party surge, INDIA alliance won 43/80 seats vs 1/80 in 2019), <b>Maharashtra</b> (Shiv Sena split consequences), and <b>Rajasthan</b> (post-state-election realignment). INDIA alliance consolidated in: <b>Tamil Nadu</b> (DMK sweep), <b>Kerala</b> (LDF hold), <b>West Bengal</b> (TMC dominance). The animation makes these geographic waves visible: watch the upper-left (UP) shift from saffron to blue, while the bottom remains stable blue.") + s("Policy") + hl("Constituencies where margins swung by >10 percentage points deserve investigation. Were swings driven by <b>candidate quality</b> (a popular local candidate), <b>anti-incumbency</b> (voters punishing the sitting MP), <b>alliance realignment</b> (party split effects), or <b>structural demographic shifts</b> (youth voter entry, migration)? Each cause implies different strategic responses for the next election.","w")

G["51"] = hd("The Great Fertility Collapse","The animation that shows humanity's most important transition.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Year-by-year bubble chart of fertility rate vs life expectancy for all countries, 1990-2023 (33 frames). <b>Bubble size = population</b>. <b>Color = continent</b>. Press play and watch three decades of demographic transformation.") + s("What Makes This the Most Important Chart") + hl("This animation compresses the <b>most consequential transformation in human history</b> into 33 seconds. The entire world is converging toward low fertility and high life expectancy. The remaining high-fertility countries (mostly West/Central Africa) will contribute the vast majority of future global population growth. <b>Whether world population peaks at 9 billion (2050) or 11 billion (2100) depends almost entirely on what happens in 20-30 African countries in the next two decades.</b>") + s("The Spatial Wave") + p("The animation reveals a <b>geographic wave of demographic transition</b>: East Asia completed first (1960s-80s), followed by Latin America (1980s-2000s), followed by South Asia (1990s-2010s). Sub-Saharan Africa entered the transition last (2000s-present). Within Africa, the wave moves from south and east (Kenya, Ethiopia, Ghana) toward west and center (Niger, DRC, Mali). The spatial sequence follows the development gradient.") + s("Policy") + hl("The single highest-leverage demographic intervention: <b>girls' secondary education in the 20-30 remaining high-fertility countries</b>. Cost: $300-500 per year per girl. Impact: 0.3-0.5 fewer births per woman per year of schooling. Countries that have achieved this (Bangladesh, Ethiopia, Rwanda) show dramatic fertility decline within a single generation. The window of opportunity is approximately 2025-2045; after that, the population momentum from today's large youth cohorts will be locked in.","w")

G["52"] = hd("The Mortality Plunge","Watch a continent lighten as millions of children survive.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated choropleth of <b>under-5 mortality</b> (per 1,000 live births) from 1990 to 2022. <b>Color scale: YlOrRd</b> (yellow = low mortality, dark red = high). Step through the animation and watch the global map gradually lighten.") + s("The MDG Acceleration") + hl("The most dramatic change occurs <b>post-2000</b>, coinciding with the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). MDG 4 set a specific target: reduce under-5 mortality by two-thirds between 1990 and 2015. While the world fell short of the two-thirds target, the progress was extraordinary: 12.7 million child deaths/year (1990) fell to 5.9 million (2015) and 4.9 million (2022). <b>This proves that internationally coordinated goals with funding commitments work</b>. The SDG framework must maintain this momentum.") + s("The Spatial Concentration of Remaining Mortality") + p("By 2022, high mortality (>80 per 1,000) is concentrated in a <b>narrow geographic band</b>: the Sahel (Mali, Niger, Chad, Burkina Faso, Nigeria), the Horn (Somalia, South Sudan), and the Great Lakes (DRC). <b>These same countries face compounding challenges</b>: conflict, food insecurity, climate vulnerability, weak governance, and geographic isolation. The 'last mile' of child survival will be the hardest because it requires operating in the world's most difficult environments.") + s("Policy") + hl("The cost-effectiveness hierarchy for child survival: (1) <b>Vaccination</b> ($10-15 per DALY), (2) <b>Oral rehydration</b> ($25/DALY), (3) <b>Bed nets</b> ($30/DALY), (4) <b>Breastfeeding promotion</b> ($50/DALY), (5) <b>Clean water/sanitation</b> ($100/DALY), (6) <b>Facility-based newborn care</b> ($500/DALY). Fund in order. The remaining high-mortality countries need all six, but resource constraints demand prioritization.","w")

G["53"] = hd("Continental Convergence and Divergence","The world is becoming more equal in health and less equal in wealth. Both facts are true simultaneously.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>Left panel</b>: life expectancy by continent (converging). <b>Right panel</b>: GDP per capita by continent (diverging). Both population-weighted.") + s("The Paradox") + hl("<b>Health convergence</b>: Africa's life expectancy rose from ~50 to ~65 years (1990-2023) while Europe's rose from ~73 to ~80. The gap narrowed from 23 years to 15. <b>GDP divergence</b>: Africa's GDP per capita rose from ~$2,000 to ~$4,500 while Europe's rose from ~$25,000 to ~$45,000. The absolute gap widened from $23,000 to $40,500. <b>These two trends coexist because health improvement is driven by technology diffusion</b> (vaccines, antibiotics, diagnostic tools cross borders easily and cheaply) <b>while wealth improvement requires institutional change</b> (governance, property rights, market infrastructure), which is locally specific and slow.") + s("Policy Implications") + hl("<b>The health convergence</b> validates the model of international health cooperation: WHO guidelines, GAVI vaccinations, Global Fund disease programmes, and bilateral health aid have demonstrably narrowed the global health gap. This model should be sustained and expanded. <b>The GDP divergence</b> challenges the assumption that 'rising tides lift all boats': economic globalization has produced enormous growth in some regions (East Asia) while leaving others behind (Sub-Saharan Africa). Closing the economic gap requires not just trade liberalization but <b>institutional development, infrastructure investment, and industrial policy</b> tailored to specific geographic and governance contexts.","w")

# 54-58: More concise but still deep
G["54"] = hd("Women's Spatial Clustering","A weak but real signal: women winners are not randomly distributed.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Left: LISA map of women winners (Moran's I = 0.062, p < 0.001). Right: area vs voter density scatter with women as pink diamonds.") + s("Interpreting Weak Spatial Autocorrelation") + hl("<b>I = 0.062</b> is weak but statistically significant (z = 4.1, p < 0.001). It means women winners are <em>slightly</em> more likely to cluster spatially than would be expected by chance. The clusters are small (2-4 adjacent constituencies) and geographically scattered (no single region dominates). The right panel confirms that women occupy a specific <b>niche in area-density space</b>: smaller, denser constituencies. <b>Policy</b>: parties could exploit the neighborhood effect by nominating women in clusters where adjacent seats have elected women, creating spatial 'beachheads' of representation that expand over election cycles.","g")

G["55"] = hd("Party Flip Pulse (3D)","The beating heart of Indian democracy: where power changed hands.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("214 constituencies that changed party between 2019 and 2024 pulse with golden rings (sinusoidal scale oscillation at different phases). Stable seats glow softly. Alliance-colored.") + s("Geographic Clustering of Flips") + hl("Flips concentrate in <b>specific geographic corridors</b>: western UP (BJP losses to SP), Maharashtra (Shiv Sena split effects), and parts of Rajasthan (post-state-election realignment). South India and Bengal show mostly stable seats. The pulsing pattern makes these corridors immediately visible: dense pulsing = volatile zone, stable glow = entrenched zone. <b>Policy</b>: campaign strategists should focus resources on the pulsing corridors (swing zones) rather than the stable zones (safe seats for either side).","g")

G["56"] = hd("Development Spiral (3D)","Countries trace helical paths through time: the DNA of development.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Gapminder data 1952-2007. Countries trace spiral paths through 3D space. <b>Radius = log(GDP per capita)</b>: outward = richer. <b>Height = life expectancy</b>: upward = healthier. <b>The year slider</b> at the bottom moves position dots along trajectory tubes.") + s("Reading the Spirals") + hl("Countries spiraling <b>outward and upward</b> = developing (most of the world). <b>Tight, low spirals</b> (small radius, low height) = stagnation (some Sub-Saharan African countries). <b>Downward dips</b> = crises (HIV/AIDS, genocide, conflict). The slider lets you identify <em>when</em> each country's development accelerated or stalled. China's spiral expands dramatically after 1978 (market reforms). India's expands after 1991 (liberalization). <b>The 3D perspective makes time visible as a physical path</b>: you can see where each country has been, where it is, and the direction it is heading.","g")

G["57"] = hd("Coral Reefs Under Siege","Linking the fever (warming oceans) to the symptom (dying reefs).") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Dual-zone visualization: <b>reef map</b> (top, 27 systems by threat level) paired with <b>SST anomaly timeline</b> (bottom, 1980-2024).") + s("Cause and Effect, Spatially and Temporally") + hl("The bottom panel shows the <b>cause</b>: accelerating ocean warming. The top panel shows the <b>effect</b>: reef systems under increasing thermal stress. The tightening interval between mass bleaching events (18, 12, 6, 8 years) is visible in the bottom timeline. Coral recovery requires 10-15 years of cool conditions. If bleaching occurs every 6-8 years, <b>reefs cannot recover between events</b>. <b>Policy</b>: marine conservation must now incorporate <em>climate triage</em>: focusing limited resources on reefs with the highest thermal tolerance and genetic diversity, while accepting that some systems will not survive under current warming trajectories.","w")

G["58"] = hd("Animated Inequality","Policy choices, not just economic forces, determine who gets what.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Gini coefficient animated by 5-year bins, 1990-2020. <b>Color: RdYlGn_r</b> (red = high inequality, green = low).") + s("The Policy Experiments") + hl("<b>Latin America's improvement</b> (Gini declining from 55-60 to 45-50): driven by conditional cash transfer programmes (Brazil's Bolsa Familia reached 50 million people; Mexico's Oportunidades reached 30 million), minimum wage increases, and expanded education access. <b>China's increase</b> (from ~35 to ~47): the inequality cost of rapid market-driven growth. Coastal provinces surged (Shanghai GDP/cap ~$30,000) while interior provinces lagged (Gansu ~$6,000). <b>Eastern Europe's varied trajectories</b>: some countries (Czech Republic, Poland) maintained moderate equality through social safety nets during transition; others (Russia, Ukraine) experienced oligarchic wealth concentration. <b>Policy lesson</b>: inequality trajectories are determined by policy choices, not economic destiny.","g") + s("Policy") + hl("The evidence shows that <b>redistribution does not necessarily harm growth</b>. Brazil maintained 3-4% annual growth while reducing Gini by 7 points (2003-2014). The IMF (2014) found that inequality above Gini ~40 actually <em>reduces</em> subsequent growth, meaning redistribution in highly unequal countries is not just equitable but economically efficient.","w")

# 3D India charts 59-64
G["59"] = hd("India Development Terrain (3D)","Eight metrics, one geography, zero excuses for any state to be complacent.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("30 Indian states as glowing pillars at geographic coordinates. <b>8 switchable metrics</b>: HDI, GSDP per capita, literacy, sex ratio, infant mortality rate, urbanization, forest cover, food production. <b>Pillar width = state area</b>. <b>Color: red (low) to green (high)</b>.") + s("What Switching Reveals") + hl("The power of this chart is in the switching. <b>HDI mode</b>: Kerala and Goa tower; Bihar and UP are short. <b>Sex ratio mode</b>: the terrain reshapes dramatically. Haryana and Punjab shrink (terrible sex ratios: 879, 895) while Kerala stays tall (1,084). <b>Food production mode</b>: Punjab and UP dominate (Green Revolution heartland). <b>Key insight: no state excels on all 8 dimensions.</b> Gujarat leads in GSDP but lags in HDI. Kerala leads in HDI but lags in GSDP. Tamil Nadu is strong across most metrics but not dominant in any. <b>Policy</b>: balanced development requires investment across all dimensions simultaneously. GDP-only growth strategies leave health, gender, and environmental deficits that eventually constrain further growth.","g")

G["60"] = hd("India Food Geography 3D","Where India grows what it eats: the Green Revolution's spatial legacy.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Rice production as <b>green diamonds</b> and wheat production as <b>gold squares</b>, placed at actual state lat/lon, with <b>height = production in million tonnes</b>.") + s("The Monsoon Boundary") + hl("The sharp rice-wheat divide follows the <b>monsoon boundary</b> (~77E longitude, roughly the Delhi-Mumbai line). <b>East of the boundary</b>: abundant monsoon rainfall supports paddy rice cultivation (Bengal, AP, Tamil Nadu, Odisha). <b>West/northwest of the boundary</b>: semi-arid conditions with canal irrigation support wheat (Punjab, Haryana, western UP). This spatial specialization is a legacy of the <b>Green Revolution</b> (1960s-70s), which introduced high-yield dwarf wheat varieties developed by Norman Borlaug, specifically suited to the irrigated conditions of Punjab and Haryana. Punjab alone produces ~17% of India's wheat on ~2% of its land.") + s("Climate Threat") + p("Both crops face spatially differentiated climate threats: <b>Wheat in Punjab</b> is vulnerable to heat stress. Every 1C increase in average temperature reduces wheat yield by 6-7%. Punjab has already experienced 0.5C warming since the 1980s. <b>Rice in Bengal</b> is vulnerable to sea-level rise and saltwater intrusion in the Sundarbans delta, plus increasing cyclone frequency. <b>Policy</b>: crop diversification (shifting some Punjab acreage to heat-tolerant millets; introducing salt-tolerant rice varieties in Bengal) is insurance against these geographically specific threats.")

G["61"] = hd("Literacy-Gender DNA Helix (3D)","When education and gender equity move together, societies transform. When they diverge, something is deeply wrong.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Two helical strands: <b>literacy (cyan)</b> and <b>sex ratio (magenta)</b>, with states ordered by HDI from bottom (lowest) to top (highest). <b>Bridges</b> connect the same state across strands.") + s("Alignment and Divergence") + hl("<b>Aligned states</b> (both strands bulge): Kerala, Goa, Himachal Pradesh. Here, education and gender equity reinforce each other in a <b>virtuous cycle</b>: educated women delay marriage, have fewer children, earn income, and invest in their daughters' education. <b>Divergent states</b> (literacy OK, sex ratio terrible): <b>Haryana</b> has ~77% literacy but a sex ratio of 879 (among the worst globally). <b>Punjab</b> has 76% literacy but sex ratio 895. These states prove that <b>education alone does not guarantee gender equity</b> when deeply rooted son preference drives sex-selective practices (ultrasound-guided sex determination followed by sex-selective abortion, despite the PCPNDT Act's prohibition).") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Haryana's mismatch</b> is the most important finding in this helix. It demands: (1) <b>Strict enforcement of the PCPNDT Act</b> (Pre-Conception and Pre-Natal Diagnostic Techniques Act) against sex-selective abortion. (2) <b>Cash incentive schemes for girl children</b> (Haryana's Ladli scheme, Beti Bachao Beti Padhao). (3) <b>Cultural change campaigns</b> targeting son preference, delivered through media, schools, and religious leaders. (4) <b>Women's economic empowerment programmes</b> to shift the perceived economic burden of daughters. The helix makes this policy argument spatial and visceral: the divergence is literally visible as the two strands pulling apart.","w")

G["62"] = hd("Constituency Aurora (3D)","Indian democracy as a breathing, living organism.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("543 constituencies as particles in 3D space. <b>Vertical oscillation amplitude = turnout</b> (higher turnout = bigger breathing motion). <b>Glow intensity = victory margin</b>. <b>Vertical beams = high-margin safe seats</b>. <b>Color = alliance</b>. The aurora breathes continuously.") + s("Interpreting the Breathing") + hl("The animation encodes democratic <b>vitality</b>: high-amplitude oscillation = engaged electorate, low amplitude = disengaged. Southern India breathes with high amplitude (turnout 65-75%), the Hindi belt oscillates gently (turnout 50-60%). <b>Beams</b> (vertical lines from high-margin seats) cluster in specific regions, indicating entrenched safe seats. <b>Halos</b> pulse around competitive seats. The overall effect: a living map of democratic intensity that reveals geographic patterns in ways that static maps cannot.","g")

G["63"] = hd("India Socioeconomic Landscape 3D","Three axes of development, one uncomfortable truth: no state has it all.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>X = Literacy rate</b>. <b>Y = GSDP per capita</b>. <b>Z = HDI</b>. <b>Bubble size = population</b>. <b>Color = region</b>. <b>Drop lines</b> to the HDI floor show each state's 'height' above minimum.") + s("What the 3D Reveals") + hl("Southern states (red) cluster at high literacy, moderate GSDP, high HDI. Northern states (green/cyan) cluster lower on all three. <b>Delhi is the critical outlier</b>: high GSDP per capita (~Rs 400,000) but moderate HDI (0.75), because Delhi's wealth is concentrated among elites while a significant fraction of its population lives in informal settlements with poor health and education outcomes. <b>Bihar occupies the lowest position on all three axes</b>: lowest literacy (64%), lowest GSDP (Rs 50,000), lowest HDI (0.57).") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>HDI is a better welfare metric than GSDP</b> because it incorporates health (life expectancy) and education (mean and expected years of schooling) alongside income. States that focus solely on GDP growth (measured by GSDP) can have poor HDI if growth is concentrated among elites (Delhi) or if health/education investment lags behind economic growth (Gujarat). <b>Bihar's position</b> at the origin of all three axes makes the case for massive, coordinated investment in literacy, healthcare, and economic opportunity simultaneously.","w")

G["64"] = hd("Gender-Development Nexus 3D","The three axes of India's gender crisis, in one rotatable space.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("<b>X = Sex Ratio</b> (females per 1,000 males). <b>Y = Infant Mortality Rate</b> (reversed: lower IMR = higher on screen = better). <b>Z = Literacy Rate</b>. <b>Color = sex ratio gradient</b> (red = dangerously low, green = healthy).") + s("The Reversed Y-Axis") + p("IMR is a <b>'bad is high' variable</b>: lower values are better. Plotting it directly would put the best states at the bottom. <b>Reversing the axis</b> (multiplying by -1 or using inverted scale) makes 'up = better' intuitive on all three axes simultaneously. This is a standard technique in multivariate visualization when one variable has opposite polarity.") + s("The Three Clusters") + hl("<b>Green/high/right corner</b> (Kerala, Goa): high sex ratio (1,000+), low IMR (<10), high literacy (>90%). These states represent the achievable ideal. <b>Red/low/left corner</b> (Haryana, Punjab, Delhi): low sex ratio (<920), moderate IMR, moderate literacy. The red color flags the gender crisis. <b>Low/low/low corner</b> (Bihar, MP, Rajasthan, UP): poor on all three dimensions, representing compounding deprivation. <b>Policy</b>: states in the red corner need PCPNDT Act enforcement + girl child incentives. States in the triple-low corner need comprehensive development investment.","w")

# WOMEN'S REPRESENTATION 66-70
G["66"] = hd("The Gauntlet: A Woman's Path Through Indian Elections","8,360 candidates entered. 458 were women. 47 survived.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Interactive funnel showing stages of elimination. <b>Stage 1</b>: ~8,360 total candidates. <b>Stage 2</b>: 458 women (5.5%). <b>Stage 3</b>: 133 women who saved their deposit (29%). <b>Stage 4</b>: 47 women who won (10.3%).") + s("Understanding Deposit Forfeiture") + hl("<b>Deposit forfeiture</b>: under Indian election law, every candidate must pay a security deposit (Rs 25,000 for General, Rs 12,500 for SC/ST categories). If the candidate receives fewer than <b>1/6 (16.7%) of total votes polled</b>, the deposit is forfeited. This is a formal indicator that the candidate was not competitive. <b>71% of women candidates (325 out of 458) forfeited their deposit</b>. This rate is significantly higher than the male forfeiture rate (~55%), suggesting that many women are fielded as <b>token candidates</b> by fringe parties with no real campaign support, organization, or media presence.") + s("What the Funnel Means") + p("The funnel narrows catastrophically at each stage. <b>Stage 1 to 2</b> (5.5% women): parties choose not to nominate women. This is the <em>gatekeeping</em> bottleneck. <b>Stage 2 to 3</b> (29% deposit-saved): most women who are nominated receive negligible support. This is the <em>resourcing</em> bottleneck. <b>Stage 3 to 4</b> (35% of deposit-saved women won): among women who received genuine support, the success rate is <b>comparable to men</b>. The problem is not that women cannot win; it is that they are not nominated and not supported.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Three interventions</b> to widen the funnel: (1) <b>Women's Reservation Bill (33%)</b>: forces parties to nominate women, addressing the gatekeeping bottleneck. (2) <b>Public funding of women candidates</b>: matching grants or campaign expense reimbursement for women, addressing the resourcing bottleneck. (3) <b>Party-level nomination quotas</b>: requiring parties to give at least 33% of their nominations (even for unreserved seats) to women, building a pipeline of experienced women politicians who will be competitive when reservation is implemented.","w")

G["67"] = hd("Gender Gap in the Electorate","Before asking why women don't win, ask how many are even registered to vote.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Diverging horizontal bar chart: <b>female voters per 1,000 male voters</b> by state. <b>Gold dashed line = parity (1,000)</b>. <b>Green = above parity</b> (more women registered than men). <b>Red = below parity</b>.") + s("What the Numbers Mean") + hl("<b>Bihar (907)</b>: for every 1,000 male voters, only 907 women are registered. Extrapolated to Bihar's ~77 million electorate, this means approximately <b>4 million women are 'missing' from voter rolls</b>. Causes: (1) Women not listed by male household heads during enumeration. (2) Married women's names removed when they migrate to husband's village. (3) Under-age registration patterns (boys registered earlier than girls). <b>Kerala (1,084)</b>: more women registered than men, reflecting higher female literacy (~96%), stronger women's autonomy, and systematic voter registration drives through women's organizations (Kudumbashree self-help groups).") + s("The Electorate Gap Precedes the Candidacy Gap") + p("Chart 65 (Silence Map) shows 152 constituencies with zero women candidates. Chart 69 shows 14 states electing zero women. But this chart reveals an even deeper problem: in states like Bihar, women are <b>not even fully registered as voters</b>, let alone running as candidates. The pipeline breaks at the very first step: democratic participation through voter registration.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Voter registration drives specifically targeting women</b> in states below 950 ratio: using women's self-help groups, ASHA (Accredited Social Health Activist) workers, and anganwadi centers as registration points. <b>Household-level enumeration reform</b>: requiring that electoral roll officers speak directly to each adult woman in the household, not just the male head. <b>Continuous electoral roll updates</b>: quarterly rather than annual, to capture women who move due to marriage. These reforms could add <b>millions of women</b> to the democratic process before any candidate-level intervention.","w")

G["68"] = hd("The Deposit Forfeiture Massacre","325 women ran. 325 women lost everything. The data behind democracy's gender failure.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Strip/jitter plot where <b>every woman candidate is a dot</b>. Three columns: <b>Red (325)</b>: deposit forfeited (<1/6 of votes). <b>Gold (86)</b>: lost but kept deposit (competitive). <b>Green (47)</b>: won. <b>Hover any dot</b> for name, party, constituency, and vote share.") + s("What the Red Wall Means") + hl("The red column of <b>325 dots</b> is the visual center of this chart. Most cluster below 2% vote share. These women were <b>not competitive</b>: many represent fringe parties (BSP nominees in southern states, unknown independent candidates, single-issue parties) that field candidates for ballot symbol recognition, not to win. They serve as <b>paper candidates</b> whose presence on the ballot counts as 'women's participation' without any genuine effort to elect them. <b>This inflates the headline number of women candidates while masking the reality that most had zero chance of winning.</b>") + s("The Gold and Green Columns") + p("<b>Gold dots (86 women)</b>: these women ran real campaigns and were competitive. They represent the actual 'glass ceiling': women who had genuine party backing, campaign infrastructure, and voter contact, but fell short. Many lost by <10 percentage points and would be competitive in a rematch with more support. <b>Green dots (47 winners)</b>: cluster at 30-55% vote share, <b>comparable to male winners</b>. When women are genuinely supported, they win at normal rates.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>The funnel from 458 to 47 is not primarily a voter problem; it is a party nomination and resourcing problem.</b> If all 458 women had received the level of support given to the average male candidate (party endorsement, campaign funds, media coverage, organizational backing), far more would have moved from red to gold, and from gold to green. A <b>'nomination responsibility' mandate</b> requiring parties to provide minimum campaign infrastructure to every candidate they nominate would prevent symbolic-only nominations.","w")

G["69"] = hd("State Scoreboard","Fourteen states elected zero women. Kerala is the most surprising.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Triple-panel horizontal bar chart. <b>Left</b>: women elected per state. <b>Center</b>: deposit forfeit rate (% of women who lost deposit). <b>Right</b>: voter gender ratio (female per 1,000 male).") + s("The Kerala Paradox") + hl("<b>Kerala elected ZERO women MPs in 2024</b> despite having: the best sex ratio in India (1,084), the highest female literacy (96%), the strongest women's self-help group network (Kudumbashree: 4.5 million women members), and the highest female voter turnout. This paradox proves that <b>voter-level gender parity does NOT automatically translate to women winning seats</b>. The pipeline breaks at the <b>party nomination stage</b>: Kerala's major parties (CPI(M), Congress, BJP) nominated very few women for Lok Sabha despite having enormous women voter bases and active women's wings. The parties calculated (correctly, in their view) that nominating men was 'safer' in competitive races.") + s("The 14 Zero-Women States") + p("States electing zero women include both small states (Goa, Meghalaya) where only 1-2 seats exist, and large states (Kerala with 20 seats) where the failure is systemic. The center panel (forfeit rate) shows that some zero-women states had 100% forfeiture: every single woman candidate lost her deposit, indicating that women were fielded only as token candidates by fringe parties.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Mandatory party-level nomination quotas</b> are more effective than voter-level interventions because <b>the bottleneck is not voter willingness to elect women but party willingness to nominate them</b>. Kerala's data proves this definitively: voters are ready (gender ratio 1,084), but parties are not (zero women nominated for winnable seats). A rule requiring parties to nominate women for at least 33% of their tickets (not just reserved seats) would immediately break the nomination bottleneck.","w")

G["70"] = hd("Women Candidature Terrain 3D","A 3D landscape of women's political exclusion across India.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Plotly 3D scatter over India's geographic footprint. <b>Height (Z-axis) = % women candidates</b> per constituency. <b>Color gradient</b>: red (0%) through orange (5%) through yellow (10%) through green (25%+). <b>Red X markers</b> pinned to the floor (z=0) mark constituencies where NO woman ran.") + s("The Terrain as Metaphor") + hl("The 3D perspective transforms abstract percentages into a <b>physical landscape</b>. Most of India is a <b>flat red desert at z=0</b> (zero or near-zero women candidates) with occasional green peaks (urban areas, southern India). The peaks are isolated: they do not form ridges or plateaus. The desert is vast and continuous. <b>This is the geography of exclusion</b>: a landscape where women's political participation is the exception, not the norm. Rotate the view to see the terrain from the south (looking north): the red desert stretches toward the Hindi heartland. Rotate to look from above: the green peaks are tiny islands in a sea of red.") + s("Spatial Pattern") + p("Women's candidature follows a <b>core-periphery pattern</b> within India: cores in metropolitan areas (Delhi, Mumbai, Bangalore, Kolkata, Chennai) and southern states (Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Karnataka); peripheries in the Hindi heartland (UP, Bihar, MP, Rajasthan). This pattern mirrors the broader development gradient but is <b>even more extreme</b>: while economic indicators show gradual spatial transitions, women's political participation shows a near-binary divide.") + s("Policy") + hl("Breaking out of the urban/southern niche requires <b>party structural reform</b>: (1) mandatory nomination quotas, (2) candidate training and mentorship programmes specifically for women in rural Hindi-belt constituencies, (3) campaign finance support targeted at women candidates in red-zone constituencies. The Women's Reservation Bill would achieve this by forcibly rotating reserved constituencies across the country, ensuring that even the reddest zones on this map must produce women MPs.","w")

# DELIMITATION & FISCAL (71, 73-80) - Charts 72 already has a deep guide

G["71"] = hd("Delimitation Simulator","India's most controversial constitutional question, made interactive.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated scatter: <b>X = current seats (out of 543)</b>, <b>Y = population-proportional new seats</b>. <b>Slider: 543 to 1000 total seats</b>. <b>Gold diagonal = no change</b>. Points above = states gaining seats. Points below = states losing. <b>Color = region</b>.") + s("The Webster/Sainte-Lague Method") + hl("Seats are allocated using the <b>Webster/Sainte-Lague method</b>, a divisor method of proportional representation. Each state's population is divided by the series 1, 3, 5, 7, 9... The resulting quotients are ranked, and seats are allocated to the highest quotients until all seats are filled. This method is less biased toward large states than the D'Hondt method and is used by many European parliaments. <b>At 543 seats</b>: UP would gain ~11 seats (from 80 to 91), TN would lose ~8 (from 39 to 31), KL would lose ~5 (from 20 to 15). The animation makes this zero-sum reallocation viscerally visible.") + s("Why Southern States Lose") + p("Southern states invested in <b>women's education, healthcare, and family planning</b> over the past 50 years. This investment succeeded: their fertility rates dropped to replacement level (TN: 1.6, KL: 1.5, AP: 1.6) while northern states remained higher (UP: 2.7, Bihar: 3.0). Under purely population-proportional delimitation, states that <b>controlled their populations are punished</b> with fewer seats, while states that did not are rewarded. This is a <b>perverse incentive</b> against demographic responsibility.") + s("Policy Options") + hl("(1) <b>Increase total seats to 700-1000</b>: reduces the proportional pain (southern states still gain absolute seats, just fewer than northern ones). (2) <b>Weight criteria beyond population</b>: area, literacy, fiscal contribution, HDI, gender development. (3) <b>Freeze the current ratio indefinitely</b> (as India did from 1976-2026 under the 42nd and 84th Amendments). (4) <b>Compensate through other mechanisms</b>: increase Rajya Sabha representation or Finance Commission transfers for states that lose Lok Sabha seats. Each option has tradeoffs between <b>democratic equality</b> (one person, one vote, requiring pure population weighting) and <b>federalism</b> (protecting states that governed responsibly). The slider lets you explore these tradeoffs quantitatively.","w")

G["73"] = hd("Women's Reservation Simulator","From 8.7% to 33% to 100%: what each step would look like.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated scatter: <b>Y = effective women % in parliament</b>. <b>Slider: 0% to 100% reservation quota</b>. Each state is a bubble. <b>Size = population</b>. <b>Color = region</b>.") + s("The Gap") + hl("<b>At 0% (current reality)</b>: 47 women MPs, 8.7% of 543 seats. India ranks 143rd globally for women's parliamentary representation (IPU 2024), behind Iraq (29%), Pakistan (20%), and Bangladesh (21%). <b>At 33% (the Women's Reservation Bill)</b>: ~181 guaranteed women seats. <b>At 50%</b>: ~272 seats. <b>At 100%</b>: all 543 seats. The 33% bill, passed by Parliament in 2023 but not yet implemented (pending delimitation), would more than triple women's representation overnight.") + s("The Evidence for Reservation") + p("Chattopadhyay and Duflo (2004), studying India's panchayati raj reservations (33% women reservation in local government), found that women leaders <b>invested more in public goods</b> (water, sanitation, roads) and were <b>less corrupt</b> (fewer bribes, more transparent budgets) than male leaders. Beaman et al. (2009, 2012) found that exposure to women leaders in reserved seats <b>reduced gender bias</b> among both men and women in subsequent elections. Reservation is not just symbolic; it produces measurably different and generally better policy outcomes.") + s("Policy") + hl("<b>Implementation of the 33% bill requires delimitation</b> (to determine which constituencies will be reserved), which in turn requires a Census (the 2021 Census was postponed due to COVID). The bill has a 15-year sunset clause, meaning it will expire if not implemented. <b>The clock is ticking</b>. Meanwhile, the animation shows that reservation is the only mechanism that reliably increases women's representation. 75 years of 'gradual voluntary change' produced an increase from ~5% (1952) to ~8.7% (2024): an improvement of less than 0.05 percentage points per year. At that rate, reaching 33% would take approximately 500 more years.","w")

G["74"] = hd("Moran's I Criteria Explorer","Which delimitation formula produces the most equitable spatial distribution of representation?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Two curves on one plot. <b>X-axis: weight given to the first variable</b> (0 = all second variable, 1 = all first variable). <b>Y-axis: Moran's I</b> (spatial autocorrelation of the resulting composite score). <b>Red curve</b>: area vs population. <b>Cyan curve</b>: women voters vs fiscal returns. <b>Gold line at I=0</b>: the ideal (no spatial clustering).") + s("How to Read the Curves") + hl("<b>Lower Moran's I = more equitable spatial dispersion</b> of representation. <b>Higher I = more clustering</b>: some regions are systematically over-represented while others are under-represented. <b>Negative I = anti-clustering</b> (ideal but unrealistic: high-value regions surrounded by low-value regions and vice versa, meaning no geographic zone is homogeneously advantaged). The curves show that <b>area-weighted allocation produces HIGHER Moran's I</b> (more clustering) because large-area states cluster geographically (Rajasthan, MP, NE India). Population weighting is slightly better. Fiscal-returns-based criteria produce consistently lower clustering.") + s("A Novel Application of Spatial Statistics to Constitutional Design") + p("This is, to our knowledge, a <b>novel application</b> of Moran's I to constitutional design. The standard debate about delimitation criteria is conducted in terms of fairness, equity, and political compromise. By reframing it as a <b>spatial optimization problem</b> (minimize Moran's I of the resulting representation distribution), we can identify criteria combinations that produce the most geographically equitable outcome, regardless of which specific states win or lose.") + s("Policy") + hl("The optimal delimitation formula would <b>minimize Moran's I</b>, meaning the formula should be chosen to produce the most spatially equitable distribution of representation. Based on these curves: (1) <b>Do not give high weight to area</b> (it increases clustering). (2) <b>Population alone is moderately equitable</b> but penalizes demographically responsible states. (3) <b>Fiscal returns and women's voter percentages</b> as supplementary criteria can reduce clustering below what population alone achieves. A combined formula (population 40%, fiscal return 25%, women's development 20%, area 15%) would likely minimize Moran's I while balancing multiple equity dimensions.","w")

G["75"] = hd("The Punishment Value","A new metric quantifying the triple burden on India's most responsible states.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("3D scatter: <b>X = fiscal return</b> (Rs per 100 paid in taxes). <b>Y = female voter %</b>. <b>Z = Lok Sabha seats</b>. <b>Color = Punishment Value</b>. <b>Size = population</b>.") + s("The Punishment Value Formula") + hl("<code>PV = 1 - 0.35 x (fiscal_return / 100)</code><br><br>Where <b>fiscal_return</b> is the Rs received per Rs 100 paid in central taxes, and <b>0.35</b> represents the estimated women's share of India's tax base. Women are approximately 35% of taxpayers (due to higher exemption thresholds and lower formal workforce participation). <b>Interpretation</b>: a PV near 1.0 (deep red) means the state faces maximum penalty. PV near 0 = break-even. PV negative = net beneficiary. <b>Tamil Nadu (PV = 0.90)</b>: pays Rs 100, gets Rs 29.7 back, women's share of the loss = 0.35 x 70.3 = Rs 24.6 per Rs 100. <b>Bihar (PV = 0.50)</b>: receives more than it pays, so the 'punishment' is mild.") + s("The Triple Burden") + p("<b>States in deep red</b> (Tamil Nadu, Maharashtra, Karnataka) face three simultaneous penalties: (1) <b>Fiscal</b>: they pay the most tax and get the least back. (2) <b>Representational</b>: under delimitation, they will lose Lok Sabha seats because they controlled population. (3) <b>Gender</b>: the women's share of the fiscal loss is uncompensated. The 3D scatter makes all three dimensions visible simultaneously.") + s("Policy Proposal") + hl("<b>Earmark 35% of each state's fiscal transfer gap</b> (the difference between what it pays and what it receives) <b>for women's welfare programmes</b> (safety infrastructure, healthcare, education, political empowerment, women police stations). For Tamil Nadu: the gap is Rs 70.3 per Rs 100 paid. 35% of this = Rs 24.6. This amount, if earmarked for women's development, would create a direct link between fiscal responsibility and gender outcomes. The proposal addresses both the fiscal and gender dimensions of the triple burden simultaneously.","w")

G["76"] = hd("Representation Inequality","A vote in Sikkim is worth six times a vote in Uttar Pradesh.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated bar chart: <b>electors per seat (millions)</b> for each state. <b>Slider: 543 to 1000 total seats</b>. <b>Perfect equity = all bars identical height</b>.") + s("The Inequality") + hl("<b>At 543 seats</b>: UP has ~2.4 million voters per seat. Sikkim has ~0.4 million. Lakshadweep has ~55,000. A vote in Sikkim is worth <b>6 times</b> a vote in UP. A vote in Lakshadweep is worth <b>44 times</b> a vote in UP. This is the <b>most fundamental democratic inequality in India</b>, more extreme than the US Senate's notorious state-size bias (Wyoming: 290K per Senator vs California: 19.5M, a ratio of 67:1, but the Senate is explicitly designed for state representation, not population proportionality; India's Lok Sabha is supposed to be population-proportional).") + s("What the Animation Shows") + p("As you drag the slider toward 1000, bars <b>equalize</b>. With more total seats, proportional allocation can assign integer seat counts that better approximate each state's population share. At ~800-1000 seats, most states converge toward ~1.0-1.5 million voters per seat. The animation makes the convergence visible: watch the tall bars (UP, Bihar, Maharashtra) shrink relative to the short bars (NE states, UTs).") + s("Policy") + hl("The question is whether India values <b>pure proportional representation</b> (one person, one vote, requiring ~800-1000 seats for reasonable equity) or <b>federal protection of smaller states</b> (accepting some inequality to ensure small states have at least 1-2 seats). The current 543-seat system is a political compromise that has not been updated since 1971. Increasing to 700-800 seats would substantially reduce inequality while remaining practically feasible (the new Parliament building has capacity for 888 members).","w")

G["77"] = hd("The Fiscal Spine","A vertebral column of inequality running the length of India.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("States connected south-to-north by latitude on the India map. <b>Node size = Lok Sabha seats</b>. <b>Node color = fiscal return</b> (red = net contributor, green = net recipient). The connecting line emphasizes the latitudinal gradient.") + s("The Spatial Co-Location of Divides") + hl("The fiscal gradient from red (south) to green (north) is <b>not an isolated phenomenon</b>. It is spatially co-located with: (1) the <b>linguistic divide</b> (Dravidian south vs Indo-Aryan north), (2) the <b>demographic divide</b> (low fertility south vs high fertility north), (3) the <b>development divide</b> (higher HDI south vs lower north), (4) the <b>political divide</b> (INDIA alliance south vs NDA north). These four divides are all latitudinally structured and spatially coincident. The spine makes this co-location visible: the same states that are red (fiscal contributors) are also the states with lower fertility, higher HDI, and INDIA alliance dominance. <b>This is not a coincidence</b>: it is the product of divergent development trajectories that began with different colonial experiences, different social reform movements (Dravidian, communist), and different post-independence policy choices (investment in education vs patronage politics).") + s("Policy") + hl("The spatial co-location of fiscal, demographic, linguistic, and political divides means that delimitation is <b>not merely an administrative question</b>. It touches the deepest identity cleavages in Indian federalism. Any delimitation formula that systematically transfers seats from south to north will also transfer them from INDIA to NDA, from Dravidian to Hindi, from low-fertility to high-fertility, and from fiscally responsible to fiscally dependent. This is why the debate is so politically explosive: it is not about numbers; it is about <b>who India is</b>.","w")

G["78"] = hd("Democratic Real Estate","Who owns how much of India's democratic space?") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Hierarchical treemap: <b>Region > State</b>. <b>Rectangle area = Lok Sabha seats</b>. <b>Color = fiscal return</b> (red = net contributor, green = net recipient). Click to drill into regions.") + s("What the Treemap Reveals") + hl("<b>Central and East regions</b> (UP 80, Bihar 40, MP 29, West Bengal 42) = large green rectangles. They receive the most fiscal transfers AND have the most seats. <b>Southern region</b> (TN 39, KA 28, KL 20, AP 25) = smaller red rectangles. They pay the most tax AND have fewer seats. The treemap makes the <b>double whammy spatial</b>: red rectangles (contributors) are literally <em>smaller</em> than green rectangles (recipients). This visual proportion directly represents the power imbalance in India's federal democracy.") + s("Policy") + hl("The treemap forces a confrontation with the structural reality: the states that <b>generate the most economic value</b> have the <b>least democratic representation</b> and <b>subsidize the states with the most representation</b>. This is not unique to India (Germany's fiscal equalization, US federal transfers, and Australian GST redistribution all involve similar dynamics), but the scale and the coincidence with ethnic/linguistic divides is uniquely combustible. <b>Constitutional reform</b> (restructuring the Finance Commission formula, reforming the Rajya Sabha, or implementing asymmetric federalism) is the only path to a durable resolution.","w")

G["79"] = hd("Fiscal Returns vs Women's Representation","Reservation fixes the gender gap. It does not fix the fiscal gap. Two problems, two solutions.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Animated bubble plot: <b>X = fiscal return</b> (Rs per 100 paid, linear scale). <b>Y = effective women %</b> (current reality + reservation mandate). <b>Slider: 0% to 100% reservation</b>. <b>Size = population</b>. <b>Color = region</b>.") + s("What the Animation Proves") + hl("As you drag the reservation slider upward, <b>all bubbles rise uniformly</b>: women's representation increases in every state. But the <b>X-axis spread does not change</b>: fiscal returns remain fixed regardless of reservation level. <b>Key insight</b>: reservation is a powerful tool for gender equity but it is <b>orthogonal to fiscal equity</b>. A state with Rs 29.7 fiscal return and 33% women MPs is still fiscally penalized. A state with Rs 142.5 and zero women MPs is still fiscally privileged. The two problems require <b>separate policy interventions</b>: (1) Women's Reservation Bill for gender. (2) Finance Commission formula reform for fiscal equity. Neither can substitute for the other.","g")

G["80"] = hd("Constituency Clustering: The Geography of Women's Exclusion","Where women contest and where they do not is not random. It is a map of India's social geography.") + s("What You Are Seeing") + p("Every constituency color-coded by <b>% women candidates</b>. Continuous scale: deep red (0%) through orange (5%) through yellow (10%) through green (25%+). <b>Size = total candidates</b>.") + s("The Spatial Clustering") + hl("<b>Red zones</b> (zero or near-zero women) cluster in: central UP (Awadhi/Bundelkhand belt), rural Bihar (Magadh/Mithila regions), parts of Rajasthan (desert belt), and rural Maharashtra (Vidarbha/Marathwada). <b>Green pockets</b> appear in: Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, Bangalore, Chennai (major metros), and much of Kerala and Tamil Nadu. The pattern mirrors India's <b>Gender Development Index</b>: the same states with the worst sex ratios, lowest female literacy, highest rates of child marriage, and most patriarchal social structures are the ones where women are systematically excluded from political competition.") + s("Why This Is Not Just Correlation") + p("The causal mechanism runs through: (1) <b>Social norms</b>: patriarchal gatekeeping in party selection committees; 'honour'-based resistance to women's public roles. (2) <b>Party structures</b>: male-dominated local party leadership that controls nominations. (3) <b>Spatial factors</b>: large, rural constituencies where campaigning requires extensive travel (mobility constraints affect women more than men); fewer media outlets (reducing the advantage of media-friendly women candidates); and traditional caste/feudal power structures that resist women's political emergence.") + s("Policy") + hl("Interventions should be <b>spatially targeted at the red zones</b>: (1) party quotas for women nominees in Hindi-belt states, (2) campaign finance support for women candidates in large rural constituencies, (3) safety infrastructure (women police stations, anti-harassment cells) in areas where women candidates face physical threats, (4) women's self-help group engagement to build a base of women politically active at the grassroots level before graduating to electoral candidacy. <b>The Women's Reservation Bill</b> would achieve this by rotation: reserved constituencies will necessarily include red-zone seats, forcing both parties and voters in these areas to experience women's political leadership.","w")
